1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 {This can be considered a modernized
version of the Rubinstein system. White makes a flexible developing move,
keeping the choice between several different development schemes in the next
moves. This move came into the limelight during the Kasparov-Karpov matches,
when the former World champion faced problems with Black against his successor
to the crown.} b6 {The most consistent answer.} (4... c5 5. g3 {usually leaves
Black struggling for equality in a sadly one-sided position.}) 5. Bd2 {This
modest-looking move is not without poison.} (5. Qb3 {[%emt 0:00:28] is
examined in Chapter 3}) ({For} 5. Bg5 {see Chapters 7-9}) 5... Bb7 6. g3 (6. a3
Bxc3 7. Bxc3 {only wastes time, allowing Black to exchange the enemy bishop.}
Ne4 8. Rc1 O-O 9. g3 d6 10. Bg2 Nd7 11. O-O Nxc3 12. Rxc3 Qe7 13. b4 a5 14. Qc2
Nf6 15. Nd2 Bxg2 16. Kxg2 {1/2-1/2 Slipak,S (2421)-Granda Zuniga,J (2650)
Buenos Aires 2018} e5 17. dxe5 (17. Re3 Ng4) 17... dxe5 $11) (6. e3 {[%emt 0:
00:02] is the subject of Chapter}) 6... O-O 7. Bg2 d6 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Rc1 {
An interesting move, preparing to unpin the knight without getting doubled
pawns.} (9. a3 {once again wastes a tempo while also weakening b3.} Bxc3 10.
Bxc3 a5 $5 (10... Ne4 11. Be1 f5 {may also be worth a try.}) 11. b4 (11. b3 Qb8
{leads to familiar play.}) 11... axb4 12. axb4 b5 $1 {The usual reaction.} 13.
cxb5 (13. c5 {Pluschke,F-Lerch,P (2370) Baden 2013 (0-1, 50)} Rxa1 14. Qxa1 Bd5
$11) 13... Nb6 (13... Rxa1 14. Qxa1 Nb6 $11) 14. Ra5 Qb8 15. Nd2 Bxg2 16. Kxg2
Nbd5 17. Qb3 Nxc3 18. Qxc3 Rxa5 19. bxa5 Qxb5 20. e4 Qe2 21. Qe3 Qh5 22. Qc3
Qe2 23. Qe3 Qh5 24. Qc3 {1/2-1/2 Grabarczyk,M (2499) -Iordachescu,V (2562)
Panormo 2001}) (9. Qc2 {has the same idea as the main move but exposes the
queen.} a5 10. Rfe1 (10. Nb5 Be4 11. Qc1 Qb8 12. Bf4 c6 13. Nc3 Bxc3 14. Qxc3
b5 15. c5 Nd5 16. Qc1 Nxf4 17. Qxf4 d5 $11) 10... Bxc3 11. Bxc3 Be4 {, with
gain of time.} 12. Qd2 Qb8 13. Rad1 (13. b3 {Grigorchuk,S (2298)-Quesada Perez,
Y (2626) Istanbul 2012 (1/2-1/2, 40)} a4 {[%cal Gb6b5] , followed by ...b6-b5.}
) (13. Qf4 b5 14. cxb5 Qxb5 15. e3 Qb7 16. Nh4 h6 17. Bxe4 Nxe4 18. Qf3 Ndf6
$17 {Kutynec,V (2305)-Megaranto,S (2532) Pardubice 2014 (0-1, 32)}) (13. Nh4
Bxg2 14. Nxg2 {Zupe,M (2272)-Danner,G (2393) Austria 2015 (1/2-1/2, 23)} b5 $11
) 13... b5 14. cxb5 Qxb5 15. Bf1 Bb7 16. Nh4 Ne4 17. Qc2 {Naumkin,I (2473)
-Fedorchuk,S (2635) Cesenatico 2011 (0-1, 37)} Rfb8 18. Rc1 a4 $15 {, with
active queenside play.}) 9... a5 10. Bg5 {The most principled move.} (10. Nb5
Bxd2 11. Qxd2 {is a bit speculative, as Black can deal with the pressure on c7.
} Rc8 12. Ne1 (12. Qe3 Qe7 13. d5 Ng4 (13... Nc5 $5 14. Nfd4 Rce8 $11) 14. Qg5
Ngf6 15. Nfd4 {Fridman,D (2618)-Marjanovic,D (2432) Baku 2016 (1/2-1/2, 50)}
Nc5 $11) 12... Bxg2 13. Nxg2 Qe7 14. Na7 Ra8 15. Nc6 Qe8 {The knight does not
cause too much trouble and Black can even consider exchanging it with ...Nb8
at a later moment.} 16. d5 (16. Rfe1 Nc5 $5 17. dxc5 Qxc6 18. cxd6 Rfd8 $11)
16... e5 $11) 10... Bxc3 {The safest move-order.} (10... h6 11. Bxf6 Nxf6 {
allows} 12. Na4 {, endangering the b4-bishop.} d5 13. c5 b5 14. c6 $5 (14. Nc3
Bxc3 15. Rxc3 $14 {also leaves White with the more pleasant position. The
difference compared to a similar position from Line 22 is that the bishop is
not outside the pawn structure.}) 14... Bxc6 15. Rxc6 bxa4 16. Qxa4 Bd6 17.
Rfc1 $14 {, with some light pressure in Livshits,R (2390) -Sulskis,S (2515)
Yerevan 1996 (1/2-1/2, 30)}) 11. Rxc3 h6 12. Bc1 $5 {The most consistent.} (12.
Bxf6 Nxf6 13. Nd2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 e5 15. dxe5 dxe5 16. Qc2 {Stupak,K (2564)
-Sasikiran,K (2666) Yerevan 2018 (1/2-1/2, 41)} Qe8 $11 {[%cal Gf6d7,Gd7c5]
Planning ...Nd7-c5.} 17. c5 $6 Nd5 18. Rf3 Qc6 $15) 12... Qb8 13. a4 {
Preventing the usual queenside plan.} c5 $1 {This is a good moment to change
plans, as White is not coordinated yet.} (13... e5 $6 14. b3 Re8 15. d5 Nc5 16.
Nd2 Qd8 17. e4 Bc8 18. h3 Bd7 19. Re3 Nh7 20. Bb2 $14 {Atalik-Marin, Chess
Stars (rapid, Internet) 2020 (1/2-1/2, 44)}) 14. b3 d5 {Since White still
needs time to get coordinated, the central structure is comfortable for Black.
The white rook and the queen are a bit exposed.} 15. Bf4 {It appears that ...
h7-h6 is useful, as White does not have Bg5.} (15. Bb2 Rd8 16. e3 (16. Qa1 cxd4
17. Nxd4 e5 18. Nf5 d4 $15) (16. cxd5 Bxd5 17. Qa1 Qb7 $11) 16... dxc4 17. bxc4
Be4 18. Qe2 Qb7 19. Rfc1 Rac8 $11) 15... Qc8 16. Ne5 (16. cxd5 Nxd5 {, with a
double attack.}) (16. dxc5 Nxc5 17. Qb1 Rd8 $11) (16. Qc2 dxc4 $1 17. Rxc4 $6
Ba6 18. Rc3 Nd5 $17) 16... Rd8 $11 {Black does not have any problems.} *

