Re1 (12. d5 Nb8 13. a4 a5) (12. Nd2 e5 13. Nb3 Qf6 14. Be2 a5 15. a4 {1/2-1/2 
(38) Coudari,C-Zuk,R Toronto 1972} Nd8 $1 $17 {Planning ...Ne6.}) 12... e5 (
12... Qf6 13. e5 dxe5 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Rxe5 c5 $11) 13. d5 $6 (13. c5 $1 bxc5
14. Rb1 Bc8 15. dxc5 Be6 $11) 13... Nb8 14. a4 a5 15. g3 Na6 16. Nh4 Nc5 17.
Ng2 Qf6 18. Re3 Rae8 19. Qc2 Bc8 $17 {[%emt 0:00:31] Koch-Cosulich,R Imperia
1973 (0-1,}) (8. Qc2 Nxc3 9. Qxc3 d6 10. Be2 Nd7 11. O-O a5 12. Nd2 O-O 13. Bf3
Bxf3 14. Nxf3 Nf6 15. Qd3 Qe7 16. e4 e5 17. d5 g6 18. b3 Nd7 19. a3 f5 $15 {
Bosnjak,P (2308)-Meier,G (2621) chess.com INT 2020 (0-1, 33)}) 8... a5 9. Ba3
Na6 $5 $146 {A slightly unusual way of developing the queen's knight in the
Dutch/Queen's Indian setup. It is justified by the bishop's presence on a3. As
we will see in the next lines, the knights are able to dominate the bishops.}
10. Be2 ({Recycling the bishop while this is still possible offers Black a
couple of free tempi:} 10. b3 f5 11. Bb2 g5 12. d5 Rf8 {, with strong
counterplay.}) (10. Bd3 {runs into} Nb4 11. Bb1 O-O 12. O-O f5 {Black's attack
is developing naturally, while White cannot play} 13. b3 {yet, as Black has}
Nc3 $15) 10... d6 $1 (10... Nb4 {is likely to cause a loss of time in the near
future.} 11. O-O O-O 12. Qc1 d6 13. b3 f5 14. Bb2 Rf6 15. a3 Na6 16. c5 Bd5 17.
Bc4 $14 {The knight does not stand well on a6 now.}) 11. O-O O-O 12. Nd2 {
One of the typical ways of fighting against the active knight.} (12. Ne1 Qg5
13. Qc1 Rfe8 14. f3 Nf6 15. Nd3 Nd7 16. Qd2 e5 17. Rad1 Qe7 18. Rfe1 e4 19. Nf4
Qg5 20. Nh3 Qg6 $11 21. f4 Nf6 22. Nf2 h5 {, and White does not have any clear
way to display activity, while Black's play is simple and natural.}) 12... Qg5
13. f4 Qh6 14. Bd3 {Continuing to fight against the intruder.} (14. Bf3 Qg6 $1)
14... Nf6 15. e4 (15. Rc1 Nb4 16. Bb1 e5 $132) 15... Nb4 16. Bxb4 axb4 17. Qe2
{White has gained space, but Black can react at once.} c5 18. d5 Rae8 19. Qf2 (
19. Qf3 e5 {leaves the knight on d2 hanging.} 20. g3 Bc8 $15 {, with strong
