1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Qb3 {White intends to play an
improved version of the Qc2 system. Before forcing the exchange on c3, he
hopes to induce a small commitment, such as 5...a5 or 5...Qe7. However, Black
can do better, and the queen will be a bit uncomfortable on b3.} c5 $1 {
Black defends the bishop, ensures a safe retreat to a5 if needed and puts
pressure on d4. Soon he will exploit the queen's position with ...Nc6 and
possibly ... Na5.} 6. dxc5 {This simplistic continuation requires a certain
accuracy from Black, mainly after White's plan initiated by the next move.} (6.
e3 {is relatively modest.} O-O 7. a3 (7. Bd3 Bb7 8. O-O Nc6 9. a3 Na5 10. Qc2
Bxc3 11. Qxc3 cxd4 12. exd4 Bxf3 13. gxf3 Rc8 14. b3 Nh5 $17 {Sokolov,I (2669)
-Eljanov, P (2693) Sarajevo 2009 (0-1, 24)}) 7... Ba5 8. Bd3 Bb7 9. O-O Bxf3
10. gxf3 cxd4 11. exd4 Bxc3 12. Qxc3 Nc6 13. Bf4 d6 $11 {In both lines we
reach a familiar structure, offering Black excellent counterplay against the
weaknesses on both wings.}) (6. Bf4 {does not put immediate pressure on the
centre.} Nc6 7. a3 (7. dxc5 Ne4 $1 8. cxb6 Qxb6 9. e3 Qa5 10. Rc1 e5 11. Bg3
Rb8 12. Qc2 Nxc3 13. bxc3 Ba3 $11 {With excellent counterplay and the better
structure. Chandler,M (2455)-Van der Wiel,J (2465) Bochum 1981 (1/2-1/2, 20)})
(7. e3 Na5 8. Qc2 cxd4 9. Nxd4 Ba6 {And White already experiences certain
queenside problems.}) 7... Na5 8. Qc2 Bxc3+ 9. Qxc3 cxd4 10. Nxd4 d5 11. cxd5
Nxd5 {The bishop also appears to be exposed on f4.} 12. Qg3 Nxf4 13. Qxf4 {
Furashev,V (2355) -Nizky,R (2426) ICCF email 2015 (1/2-1/2, 31) With a
comfortable advance in development for Black.} O-O $15) (6. a3 Ba5 {transposes
to any of the next lines.}) (6. Bg5 {is examined in Chapters 4 to 6}) 6... bxc5
{Black maintains his outpost.} (6... Bxc5 {is also playable, but the main
problem remains} 7. Bf4 {followed by Rd1, with certain pressure in the centre.}
) 7. g3 {A plan advocated by Mamedyarov.} (7. a3 Ba5 8. Bg5 h6 9. Bh4 {allows
Black to use the open b-file with} Qb6 10. Qc2 Ne4 $1 11. Qxe4 $2 Qxb2) ({If} 
7. Bg5 h6 8. Bh4 {, Black can once again take advantage of the early exchange
on c5 with} Qa5 $1) (7. Bf4 {is no more impressive than one move earlier.} Nc6
8. e3 O-O 9. Rd1 (9. Bd6 Re8 {, followed by ...e6-e5, endangers the bishop.})
9... Re8 {Inhibiting Bd6.} 10. Bg5 Rb8 {The b-file is once again useful for
Black.} 11. Bd3 Ba5 12. Qa3 Qb6 13. Bxf6 (13. Rd2 Qb4 14. Qxb4 Nxb4 15. Bb1
Nbd5 $1 {Threatening ...Bxc3.} 16. Bxf6 Nxf6 $15) 13... Qxb2 14. Qxb2 Rxb2 15.
O-O gxf6 $17 {Dlugolecki,G (1530)-Kuzmin,K (2115) LSS email 2013 (0-1, 52)})
7... Nc6 8. Bg2 O-O $5 $146 {At this stage, it is useful to remain flexible.
Hurrying to attack c4 may result in a small initiative for White.} (8... Ba6 9.
O-O O-O 10. Bf4 Na5 (10... d5 $6 11. Qa4 Qb6 12. Nb5 $14 {Mamedyarov,S (2772)
-Jakovenko,D (2698) Jerusalem 2019 (1/2-1/2, 33)}) 11. Qa4 Bxc4 12. Bd6 {
, with obvious compensation for the pawn. Silman,J (2345)-Browne,W (2495) New
York 1987 (0-1, 48)}) (8... O-O 9. O-O Na5 10. Qc2 Nxc4 11. Na4 d5 12. a3 Ba5
13. b3 Nd6 14. Nxc5 Bb6 15. Bb2 Bxc5 16. Qxc5 Ba6 {Black's position is solid,
and objectively he may have equalised, but the general feeling is that White's
play is more pleasant.}) 9. O-O Bxc3 {This looks like a small concession, but
Black wishes to rid himself of the annoying knight.} 10. Qxc3 Qb6 {One
important point is that White's plan based on Bg2 is a bit one-sided. If he
fails to get dynamic play, he will have no chances of an advantage.} 11. Bf4 (
11. Bg5 Ne4 $11) (11. Qb3 Bb7 12. Bg5 Ne4 13. Bf4 d6 14. Rfd1 e5 $11) (11. b3
Bb7 12. Bb2 Rfe8 13. Rad1 e5 $11 {, followed by ...Rad8. The threat ...Nd4 is
in the air, and in some cases ...d7-d5 would yield Black the initiative.
Sooner or later, White will have to offer the exchange of the light-squared
bishops, leaving Black with a strategically comfortable position.}) 11... Bb7
12. Rfd1 Rfe8 13. e3 $5 {[%cal Gf3e5] Preparing Ne5 without fearing ...Nd4.} (
13. Bd6 e5 $1) (13. Rac1 e5 14. Bg5 Nd4 $17) 13... e5 $1 {A promising pawn
sacrifice.} 14. Nxe5 Nxe5 15. Bxe5 Bxg2 16. Bxf6 (16. Kxg2 $2 Ne4 $19) 16...
Bh3 17. Bxg7 Qg6 18. Bh8 Re6 {White's king is more vulnerable than Black's,
and the bishop on h8 is hanging. These factors ensure Black enough
compensation for the pawn.} 19. Rxd7 h6 {Threatening ...Kh7.} 20. e4 (20. Rad1
Rae8 21. Rd8 Rxd8 22. Rxd8+ Kh7 23. e4 Rxe4 24. Rd6 Re1+ 25. Qxe1 Qxd6 26. Bc3
Qc6 27. f3 Qxf3 28. Qf2 Qd1+ 29. Be1 f6 30. Qe3 Qc2 $11 {Black does not have
any problems holding a draw.}) 20... Rae8 {[%cal Gg8h7]} 21. Rad1 Rxe4 22. Rd8
Kh7 23. Rxe8 Rxe8 24. Bf6 Re6 25. Bh4 Qe4 26. f3 Qe2 27. Qd3+ Qxd3 28. Rxd3 Re2
29. Bf6 Rg2+ 30. Kh1 Rc2 31. Rd1 Kg6 32. Bc3 h5 {Despite his extra pawns,
White cannot free himself. Black can count on a positional draw.} *

