1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Qb3 c5 6. Bg5 {The most active and
popular move. White puts indirect pressure on the centre without releasing the
tension.} Bb7 {It is important to delay ...h7-h6 in order to keep the
g5-bishop vulnerable to ...Bxc3+, and if Qxc3 then ...Ne4. This works only if
White has the rook on d1 or the other bishop on e2, in the knight's path.} 7.
e3 {The most natural way of continuing development.} (7. dxc5 {After White has
committed his bishop to g5, Black can answer} Bxc5 $5 8. Rd1 (8. e3 O-O {
transposes to a line from the comment on the next move.}) 8... h6 9. Bh4 O-O {
White has more space but is behind in development. Black mainly relies on his
active minor pieces.} 10. Qc2 {Preparing e2-e4.} (10. e4 g5 11. Bg3 Nxe4 $15) (
10. e3 Be7 11. Be2 Na6 {transposes to the line from the next comment.}) 10...
Be7 11. e4 Na6 12. Be2 Nc5 13. Bxf6 $1 {The only way to keep fighting for a
small advantage. Other moves yield Black easy play.} (13. Nd2 d5 14. cxd5 exd5
15. e5 Nfd7 16. Bg3 d4 $17) (13. e5 Nfe4 $11) 13... Bxf6 14. e5 Be7 15. b4 Na6
16. a3 Nb8 17. Ne4 a5 18. Nd6 {The only way to maintain control over c5.} Bxd6
19. exd6 axb4 20. axb4 Nc6 {But not for long.} 21. b5 {Trying to keep the
knight out of play.} (21. Qc3 Qf6) (21. Qb3 Qf6 22. O-O Ne5 {With at least
equal play.}) 21... Na5 22. Ne5 Rc8 23. Qd3 Rc5 24. f4 f6 25. Ng6 Nxc4 $1 26.
Ne7+ Kh8 27. Ng6+ Kg8 $11 28. Nxf8 $2 Qxf8 29. Qd4 Bd5 $5 $15) (7. a3 Ba5 {
Transposes to Chapter 5}) 7... O-O 8. Bd3 {White tries to keep the e2- and
d1-squares clear, to avoid the freeing manoeuvre ...Bxc3+ followed by ...Ne4.
In doing so, he leaves the knight on f3 vulnerable.} (8. dxc5 Bxc5 9. Be2 Be7
10. O-O Na6 $5 {The simplest way to equality.} ({Black can also switch to a
Hedgehog with} 10... d6 11. Rfd1 Nbd7 12. Qc2 a6 13. Rac1 Qc7 14. Qb1 Rac8 15.
Nd2 Ne5 16. Bf4 {Khegay,D (2375)-Bocharov,D (2575) Nizhnij Tagil 2014 (1/2-1/2,
40)} Rfd8 $11) 11. Rfd1 Nc5 12. Qc2 Nfe4 $11 13. Bxe7 (13. Bf4 Nxc3 14. Qxc3 g5
15. Bg3 f5 $132) 13... Qxe7 14. Nxe4 Bxe4 15. Qd2 a5 {Consolidating the knight.
} (15... d5 $5 16. b4 Nb7 17. Nd4 dxc4 18. f3 e5 19. fxe4 exd4 20. exd4 Rac8
21. e5 c3 22. Qc2 Qxb4 $11 {With interesting play. De (0-1, 43)Carlos Arregui,
I (2346)-Horvath,A (2409) ICCF email 2006}) 16. Nd4 Rfd8) (8. Rd1 Bxc3+ {and})
(8. Be2 cxd4 {(, followed by ...Bxc3+) are practically identical to the lines
with the insertion of a2-a3 and ...Ba5 examined later. While in the latter
line the bishop is hanging, White does not obtain anything after} 9. Qxb4 Nc6
10. Qa3 dxc3 11. Qxc3 Ne4 12. Bxd8 Nxc3 13. Bxb6 Nxe2 14. Bc5 Rfc8 15. Kxe2 Na5
16. Bd4 Nxc4 {Vecek,M (2140)-Leonard,A (2137) ICCF email 2011 (1/2-1/2, 25)}) (
8. a3 Ba5 {is examined in Line 27.}) 8... cxd4 {The best reaction after Bd3.}
9. exd4 (9. Nxd4 Na6 10. O-O Be7 11. Be2 Nc5 12. Qd1 a6 13. Rc1 Rc8 14. Bf3
Bxf3 15. Qxf3 {0-1 (24) Schiffer,K (2316) -Kistella,R (2329) Goch 2005} (15.
Nxf3 h6 16. Bh4 d6) 15... Nd3 16. Rc2 Ne5 17. Qb7 Nxc4 18. Qxa6 Nxb2 19. Rxb2
Rxc3 20. Bxf6 (20. Rxb6 Nd5 $15) 20... Bxf6 21. Rxb6 Bxd4 22. exd4 d5 $15) (9.
Qxb4 Na6 10. Qa3 dxc3 11. Qxc3 Nc5 12. Bc2 Rc8 13. Qd4 (13. Bxf6 Qxf6 14. Qxf6
gxf6 $11) 13... h6 (13... d5 14. cxd5 Bxd5 15. O-O Bxf3 16. Qxd8 Rfxd8 17. gxf3
h6 18. Bh4 Nd3 $11) 14. Bxf6 Qxf6 15. Qxf6 gxf6 16. Nd4 a5 17. b3 Rfd8 18. O-O
f5 19. f3 d5 $15 {Black is very active and the bishop on c2 is out of play and
even vulnerable, Poluljahov,A (2510) -Dokhoian,Y (2570) Igalo 1994 (1/2-1/2,
35)}) 9... Be7 10. O-O-O {This exposes the king along the c-file.} ({But the
king does not feel better after} 10. Rd1 {either:} Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nc6 12. Bb1 d5
13. f4 g6 14. cxd5 Nxd5 15. Bh6 Re8 16. Ne2 Bf8 $17 {With a huge positional
advantage. Ivanisevic,I (2540)-Bojkovic,N (2427) Skopje 2002 (1-0, 45).}) 10...
Nc6 (10... Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nc6 {is also good.}) 11. d5 Na5 (11... Nxd5 12. cxd5
Bxg5+ 13. Kb1) 12. Qc2 {Kogan,A (2560) -Pantani playchess.com INT 2006 (1-0,
67)} exd5 13. cxd5 h6 14. h4 Re8 $13 {Followed by ...Rc8, with enough
counterchances.} *

