{[%evp 0,42,15,15,27,11,13,21,29,29,20,9,26,-12,0,12,11,-4,13,-20,-13,-2,-8,-8,
-8,9,10,9,15,9,8,2,0,5,23,9,12,10,10,10,13,18,13,9,35]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Qb3 c5 6. Bg5 Bb7 7. e3 O-O 8. a3 Ba5 {These moves could
have been inserted at an earlier stage, too, with a transposition to the
current line. In some cases, the bishop could be more exposed here, but in
others it stands better than on b4, as ...cxd4 is possible. Finally, there are
situations when there is no real difference compared to the positions without
the last two moves.} 9. Rd1 (9. Bd3 {offers Black more freedom than 8. Bd3, as
after} Bxf3 10. gxf3 {Black can first take on d4.} cxd4 11. exd4 Nc6 12. Qd1
Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Re8 {Threatening ...e6-e5.} 14. O-O Rc8 15. Kh1 Ne7 16. Bxf6
gxf6 17. Rg1+ Ng6 18. Qd2 f5 {With excellent play.}) (9. dxc5 {may seem like a
logical consequence of the previous move, as the b6-pawn is hanging. However,
Black has} Na6 $1 10. Qc2 (10. cxb6 Nc5 11. Qc2 Be4 12. Qd1 Bxc3+ 13. bxc3 Qxb6
$17 {White has an awful structure and is behind in development.}) (10. Nd2 Nxc5
{With the bishop on b4, this would not be possible, of course.} 11. Qc2 Bxc3
12. Qxc3 Rc8 {[%cal Gd7d5] Planning ...d7-d5, when the queen and the c4-pawn
would be in some danger.} 13. b4 Nce4 14. Nxe4 Nxe4 15. Bxd8 Nxc3 16. Bh4 f6 {
The position is about equal. With his development incomplete and the queenside
light squares weak, White cannot enjoy his bishop pair.} 17. f3 Na4 18. Bg3 d5
19. cxd5 Bxd5 20. Ba6 Rc2 21. O-O Bc4 22. Bxc4 Rxc4 23. Rfd1 h5 24. h4 Nc3 $11)
(10. c6 $5 {lures the bishop onto a more exposed square, but this does not
yield much.} Bxc6 11. Qc2 Bxc3+ 12. Qxc3 Nc5 13. Nd2 Rc8 14. b4 Nce4 15. Nxe4
Nxe4 16. Bxd8 Nxc3 17. Bh4 f6 {With similar play as in the previous line.})
10... Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 Nxc5 12. Bxf6 Qxf6 13. Qxf6 gxf6 14. Be2 a5 15. Nd4 Rfd8
16. O-O a4 17. f3 Kf8 18. Rac1 Ke7 $11 {Lodhi,M (2475) -Tiviakov,S (2630)
Kolkata 1994 (0-1, 69)}) (9. Be2 {is Chapter 7}) 9... Bxc3+ {With the rook
exposed on d1, this is a typical reaction.} 10. bxc3 {Obviously a small
concession.} ({However,} 10. Qxc3 {leads to simplifications and does not
prevent getting doubled pawns, either.} Ne4 11. Bxd8 Nxc3 {Exploiting the
hanging position of the rook.} 12. bxc3 Rxd8 {Black has the better structure
and White should use his pressure along the d-file to keep the balance.} 13. d5
Re8 $1 (13... d6 $2 14. dxe6 fxe6 15. Ng5 Bc8 16. Bd3 h6 17. Be4 $18) 14. Be2
d6 15. O-O (15. dxe6 Rxe6 $15) 15... Nd7 16. Rd2 e5 $11 {Black does not have
any problems at all.}) 10... Qe7 11. Be2 {The bishop belongs here to inhibit
Black's kingside expansion.} (11. Bd3 h6 12. Bh4 d6 13. O-O {Szeberenyi,A 
(2401)-Broomfield,M (2255) Budapest 2003 (1/2-1/2, 15)} Nbd7 14. Nd2 g5 15. Bg3
Nh5 16. Be2 {White needs to play this sooner or later to force the exchange on
g3.} (16. a4 f5 $15) 16... Nxg3 17. fxg3 f5 $5 {With complicated play and
roughly equal chances.}) 11... d6 12. O-O Nbd7 13. Nd2 h6 14. Bh4 e5 {Starting
to place all the pawns on the dark squares in order to restrict the bishop.}
15. Rde1 g5 16. Bg3 Ne8 {Clearing the path of the f-pawn and intending to
transfer the knight to e6.} 17. e4 Ng7 18. d5 (18. Qc2 Ne6 19. dxe5 (19. d5 Nf4
20. Bg4 Nf6 21. Bf5 Bc8 $15) 19... dxe5 20. f3 h5 $15) 18... Nf6 19. Qd1 Bc8
20. h3 Bd7 21. Bh2 Kh8 {While it is not clear how Black will carry out his
attack yet, it is obvious that White can do little but sit and wait. Lipinsky,
F (2331)-Yu,S (2435) Budapest 1999 (0-1, 34).} *

