1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Qb3 c5 6. Bg5 Bb7 7. e3 O-O 8. a3
Ba5 9. Be2 {This is another move that puts a piece on the f6-knight's
trajectory, but Black's reaction is a bit different.} cxd4 $1 (9... Bxc3+ $6
10. Qxc3 Ne4 11. Bxd8 Nxc3 {runs into} 12. Bxb6 axb6 (12... Nxe2 13. Bxc5 $18)
13. bxc3 $14 {Black may have insufficient compensation for the pawn, as b6 is
weak.}) 10. exd4 {Trying to keep the central space advantage.} ({Black can meet
} 10. Nxd4 {in many ways, but the simplest is} Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 ({If} 11. bxc3 $6
{Black may even consider} Bxg2 12. Rg1 Be4 {, followed by ...Na6.}) 11... Ne4
12. Bxd8 Nxc3 13. Be7 Nxe2 14. Kxe2 (14. Bxf8 Nxd4 {loses material. Beautiful
but lethal alignment of the white pieces on the enemy knight's path.}) 14...
Rc8 15. Rac1 Ba6 {White is already struggling to prove compensation for the
pawn.} 16. Kd2 (16. b3 d5 $17) 16... Bxc4 17. b3 Ba6 18. Rxc8+ Bxc8 19. Rc1 Nc6
{The simplest.} (19... Na6 20. b4 {leaves the knight passive.}) 20. Nxc6 dxc6
21. Rxc6 Bb7 22. Rc7 Bxg2 {White does not have any problems reaching a draw,
but cannot hope for more, of course.}) 10... Bxc3+ 11. Qxc3 (11. bxc3 h6 12.
Bh4 Nc6 {yields Black good play against White's weaknesses.} 13. Nd2 (13. O-O
Na5 14. Qb4 {Blondel,F (1934)-Ilyasov,A (2330) ICCF email 2015 (0-1, 49)} Bxf3
15. Bxf3 Rc8 16. c5 Nc6 17. Qa4 bxc5 18. dxc5 Ne5 19. Be2 Qc7 20. Bxf6 gxf6 21.
Qh4 Kg7 $17) 13... Na5 14. Qb4 Qc7 15. Bxf6 gxf6 16. O-O Rac8 17. Rfe1 f5 {
Preventing Ne4 after the planned ...Ba6.} 18. Rad1 Ba6 19. d5 Bxc4 20. Nxc4
Nxc4 21. Rd4 {Gerbich,V (2454)-Bozyavkin,A (2438) ICCF email 2013 (1/2-1/2, 37)
} Ne5 22. Ba6 Rb8 23. Rh4 Ng6 24. Rxh6 Kg7 25. Rh3 Rh8 $11 {=/+ Black has
repelled the attack and enjoys absolute stability.}) 11... Ne4 {After the
exchange on d4, this works out well.} 12. Bxd8 (12. Qe3 {just misplaces
White's pieces.} Nxg5 13. Nxg5 d5 14. O-O h6 15. Nf3 dxc4 16. Bxc4 {1/2-1/2
Vallejo Pons,F (2554)-Pert, N (2455) Aviles 2000} Nc6 17. Rad1 Ne7 $15 {
With a comfortable isolani position for Black, as he has managed to exchange
two minor pieces.}) 12... Nxc3 13. Be7 ({The point is that after} 13. Bxb6 Nxe2
14. Bc5 {, the knight already has an escape:} Nf4 $1 $19 {, with a decisive
material and positional advantage.}) 13... Re8 14. Bd6 Nxe2 15. Kxe2 {All
these exchanges have helped Black, of course, but the active white bishop is a
bit unpleasant.} Nc6 {Developing and inviting White to think about ...Na5.} 16.
b4 (16. b3 f6 {Preparing the knight's transfer to f7, even though Black will
change his intentions later.} 17. Rhd1 Rac8 18. Rac1 Nd8 19. a4 g5 20. h3 h5
21. Ne1 Rc6 22. Bb8 d5 23. Bxa7 dxc4 24. bxc4 Ba6 25. Nd3 (25. Kd3 Nb7 $19)
25... Re7 26. Bb8 Bxc4 27. Ke3 Rb7 28. Nb4 Rc8 $17 {Lehtinen,P (2176)
-Siikaluoma,A (2271) ICCF email 2006 (0-1, 44)}) 16... f6 {A familiar move,
and this time Black will continue his initial plan until its end.} 17. Rhd1 Nd8
18. a4 Rc8 19. Rac1 Nf7 20. Bf4 g5 21. Be3 Kg7 22. b5 a6 23. h4 h6 24. g3 axb5
25. axb5 Nd6 26. Nd2 Rc7 27. Kd3 Rec8 28. Rc3 {1/2-1/2 Lindstrom,B (2415)
-Torsteinsson,T ICCF email 2011 The position is statically and dynamically
balanced.} *

