-7,-7,-15,0,0,0,0,-36,-58,-8,-57,3,-39,-35,-35,-40,-11,-5,-264,-264,-226,-228,
-338,-343]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg5 {This is the most
aggressive variation after 4.Nf3 b6 and precisely the one Kasparov repeatedly
used against Karpov. White does not mind having doubled pawns on the c-file,
as he hopes that the more or less forced kingside weakening with ...h7-h6 and .
..g7-g5 will offer him chances to take over the initiative.} Bb7 6. Nd2 $5 {
This used to be fashionable at some point. White intends to occupy the centre
with pawns without losing time with e2-e3 (f2-f3 and e2-e4). However, the last
move looks a bit weird strictly from a developing point of view.} (6. Qc2 h6 7.
Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 {is likely to transpose to the main system examined in Lines
30 and 31.}) (6. Rc1 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 {reaches a worsened version of
the aforementioned lines, as the rook is not doing much on c1.}) (6. Qb3 c5 {
transposes to any of the Chapters 4-6. This is one of the reasons Black should
not hurry with ...h7-h6 in the actual line, as he needs to keep the
possibility of ...Bxc3 followed by ...Ne4.}) (6. e3 {is the main continuation,
examined in Chapters 8 and 9.}) 6... h6 7. Bh4 e5 $5 {An unexpected move,
taking advantage of the fact that White has neglected his development and
weakened his control in the centre.} ({White's idea would be justified after} 
7... Bxc3 8. bxc3 d6 9. f3 Nbd7 10. e4 {, even though Black's position would
remain solid and playable.}) 8. dxe5 {The critical answer, but practice has
shown that it is likely to lead to trouble.} (8. e3 {offers Black active piece
play.} exd4 9. exd4 O-O 10. Be2 Nc6 11. a3 Be7 12. Nf3 Ne4 13. Nxe4 Bxh4 $11) (
8. d5 {is comfortable for Black, too.} Bxc3 9. bxc3 d6 10. e3 g5 11. Bg3 Nbd7
12. Bd3 Nc5 13. Bf5 {Suleymanli,A (2313)-Abasov,N (2629) Baku 2018 (1-0, 28)}
Bc8 $15) (8. a3 exd4 $5 {In the Nimzoindian, Black usually plays this
intermediate move with his c-pawn.} ({The untested} 8... Bxc3 9. bxc3 Qe7 {
looks fine for Black, too.}) 9. axb4 dxc3 10. bxc3 d6 {Optically, White has
consolidated his queenside space advantage, but his structure is not perfect.}
11. e4 (11. f3 Nbd7 12. e4 Ne5 13. Bf2 O-O 14. Be2 Nh5 15. g3 f5 {, with
strong counterplay. Indjic,A (2618)-Kovalev,V (2648) lichess.org INT 2020 (0-1,
41)}) 11... Nbd7 12. f4 Qe7 13. Bd3 g5 14. Bg3 (14. fxg5 hxg5 15. Bxg5 Qe5 16.
Bxf6 Qxf6 $17 {leaves White underdeveloped and weak on the dark squares.})
14... gxf4 15. Bxf4 Ne5 16. Bc2 {Svetushkin,D (2605)-Soltanici,R (2382)
Kishinev 2019 (0-1, 39)} a6 17. O-O O-O-O 18. Qe2 Rde8 $11) (8. Qb3 exd4 9.
Qxb4 {allows Black to gain a tempo for his knight development. He has two
possible moves.} Nc6 {may lead to sharper play.} (9... Na6 {The solid way.} 10.
Qa3 dxc3 11. Qxc3 Qe7 (11... g5 12. Bg3 Qe7 $2 13. Be5 $18) 12. O-O-O O-O-O 13.
f3 (13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. e3 f5 $15 {offers Black activity all over the board,
despite his imperfect structure.}) 13... d5 $5 14. e3 g5 15. Bf2 Rhe8 $11 {
With better development and perfect centralisation, compensating for the
bishop pair.}) 10. Qb3 g5 11. Bg3 dxc3 12. Qxc3 Qe7 {The difference compared
to the previous line is that Be5 is not available.} 13. Ne4 {More or less
forced.} (13. O-O-O O-O-O $15) (13. Bxc7 $2 d6 $19) 13... Qxe4 14. Qxf6 Rg8 15.
e3 (15. Bxc7 Rg6 16. Qc3 d6 $19 {again traps the bishop.}) 15... Qc2 ({
Preparing this incursion with} 15... d6 {is also possible.} 16. h4 Qc2 17. hxg5
Rg6 18. Qh8+ Kd7 19. Qh7 Rf8 20. Rxh6 Qxb2 21. Rd1 Qb4+ {With a perpetual.})
16. Bxc7 Rg6 17. Qc3 Qxc3+ 18. bxc3 d6 19. c5 {The only way to save the bishop.
} bxc5 20. Rb1 Bc8 21. Bb5 Kd7 22. Ba5 {The bishop is slightly strangely
placed, of course.} Bb7 ({I am reluctant to give} 22... g4 {as the mainline,
