1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg5 Bb7 6. e3 {The most natural and
probably best move, leading to consistent play.} h6 7. Bh4 g5 (7... Bxc3+ 8.
bxc3 d6 {used to be Karpov's favourite, but now and at a later stage I prefer
to keep the "mirrored Dragon" structure intact, meaning with the pawn on d7.})
8. Bg3 Ne4 9. Qc2 (9. Nd2 $5 {is an interesting pawn sacrifice, which Black
does not need to accept, though.} Bxc3 (9... Nxc3 10. bxc3 Bxc3 11. Rc1 Bb4 12.
h4 $44 {offers White obvious compensation.}) 10. bxc3 Nxg3 11. hxg3 {White has
spared the tempo Qc2, but it is questionable that this can offer him an
advantage. After all, he has also retreated with the knight without being
pushed to it.} Nc6 12. e4 (12. f4 {is a bit optimistic, as it weakens the
g-file.} Qe7 13. Be2 O-O-O 14. c5 Rdg8 15. Bf3 h5 $1 16. Nb3 {Atalik,S (2585)
-Marin,M (2530) Timisu de Sus 1998 (1/2-1/2, 17).} h4 $1 17. g4 f5 $19) 12...
Qe7 (12... e5 $5 13. Nb3 Qf6) 13. Bd3 O-O-O 14. Qe2 {In his comments to our
game, Atalik recommended this as slightly better for White.} Qa3 $1 {It
appears that the queen on c2 would play an important part after all.} ({
Actually, the neutral} 14... Kb8 {is also OK for Black.} 15. Nb3 d6 16. g4 Qf6
17. a4 a5 18. Rb1 Ka7 19. Kd2 {Wojtaszek,R (2606)-Alekseev,E (2632) Istanbul
2005 (0-1, 57)} Nb8 20. Qe3 Nd7 21. f3 c5 $11 {Black has stabilised the
position and has no worries at all.}) 15. Nb3 h5 $1 {Planning ...h5-h4.} (15...
Na5 16. O-O $5) 16. Rxh5 Na5 $1 {Suddenly, White is under pressure on both
wings, while the black king is absolutely safe.} 17. Rb1 Rxh5 18. Qxh5 Qxa2 19.
Nxa5 (19. Nd2 Ba6 20. Qe2 Rh8 $19) 19... Qxa5 20. Rc1 Ba6 $15 21. Qxf7 $2 Qa3
22. Rc2 (22. Kd2 $2 Rf8) 22... Qa4 23. Kd2 Bxc4 $17) 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 Nxg3 (
10... d6 11. Bd3 f5 {is more popular, when} 12. d5 {leads to huge
complications. Now you may understand why I am reluctant to weaken e6 with ...
d7-d6 at an early stage.}) 11. hxg3 {The classical approach. White captures
towards the centre and opens the h-file for his rook.} (11. fxg3 {is examined
in Chapter 9}) 11... Nc6 12. g4 {As we will see, this blockade is not too
reliable. White has tried a wide range of moves, but none of them causes Black
serious problems.} (12. Bd3 Qe7 13. Rb1 (13. O-O-O O-O-O 14. g4 Na5 15. Rh5 {
Ng,J (1246)-Koo,W (1822) Puchong 2017 (1/2-1/2, 25)} c5 16. Rdh1 Qf6 {White
starts to hang.} 17. dxc5 bxc5 18. Qb2 Bc6 19. Qa3 Nb7 20. Kb2 Kc7 $17 {
White's initiative has reached a dead end and his structural problems stay.})
13... g4 14. Nd2 (14. Nh4 {typically leaves the knight out of play for a long
time.}) 14... h5 15. Rh4 {Preventing ...h5-h4.} f5 16. f4 $6 {Just helping
Black to open files for his attack.} gxf3 17. gxf3 O-O-O 18. Kf2 Rdg8 19. Rbh1
Qg7 $1 {It is important to leave the g5-square clear for... the knight!} (19...
Qg5 20. R1h3 $11 {Vokac,M (2440)-Marinelli,T (2365) Brno 1991 (1-0, 42)}) 20.
R1h3 (20. Nf1 Qf7 {[%cal Gc6e7] , followed by ...Ne7-g6.}) 20... Nd8 $15 {
, followed by ...Nf7-g5, with a strong initiative.}) (12. Nd2 Qe7 13. Nb3 f5
14. Bd3 Qf6 15. f3 {Ribli,Z (2590)-Petrosian,T (2605) Las Palmas 1982 (1/2-1/2,
18)} h5 {The natural way of continuing the kingside attack.} 16. a4 O-O-O 17.
a5 h4 18. g4 (18. gxh4 Rxh4 19. Rxh4 gxh4 $15 {leaves the pawn on g2
vulnerable.}) 18... fxg4 19. fxg4 Rdf8 $15 {With very pleasant play for White.}
) (12. Rh5 {is another way to fight for the blockade.} Qf6 13. g4 O-O-O (13...
Ne7 14. Nd2 {ensured White some domination in Ionescu,C (2520) -Kengis,E (2485)
Timisoara 1987 (1-0, 35)} Ng8 15. Be2 Qg7) 14. Nd2 Rdf8 15. Bd3 Qe7 16. O-O-O
Na5 {Black prepares to break with ...f7-f5 by putting pressure on c4 and
clearing the bishop's diagonal.} 17. Rh2 (17. Kb1 f5 $1 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Bxf5
Nxc4 $1 20. Nxc4 Rxf5 $1 $19) (17. Kb2 f5 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Bxf5 Bxg2 $15) (17.
f3 f5 {leaves the e3-pawn hanging.}) 17... f5 18. gxf5 exf5 19. Bxf5 Qa3+ 20.
Kb1 Rxf5 21. Qxf5 Rf8 22. Qe5 {White needs to keep his queen active, as
otherwise Black's attack would become too strong.} (22. Qd3 $2 Rxf2 23. Rxh6
Bxg2 $17) (22. Qc2 $6 Rxf2 $17) 22... Qxc3 23. Qe7 Qd3+ {, with a perpetual.})
(12. Rb1 Qe7 {At this stage Black plays a bit hesitantly.} (12... Qf6 $5 13. c5
h5 14. Be2 h4 15. gxh4 gxh4 $11) 13. c5 h5 14. Be2 Na5 (14... h4 $5) 15. Nd2 $6
(15. c4 $1 {looks active for White.}) 15... Bxg2 16. Rxh5 O-O-O 17. cxb6 axb6
18. Rxh8 Rxh8 19. Bf3 Bxf3 20. Nxf3 Qf6 21. Ke2 Nc4 $19 {Black is more active
and has the better structure. Gheorghiu,F (2605)-Miles,A (2620) London 1980 
(0-1, 30)}) 12... Qe7 13. Nd2 {Transferring the knight to the queenside.} (13.
Bd3 O-O-O 14. c5 h5 $5 15. gxh5 g4 16. Nd2 f5 17. cxb6 axb6 18. Nf1 Qg5 19. Ng3
Ne7 20. Rh2 Nd5 {Threatening ...f5-f4.} 21. c4 Nb4 22. Qd2 Nxd3+ 23. Qxd3 Rdf8
24. Rb1 (24. O-O-O f4 25. exf4 Rxf4 26. Qe3 Qf6 27. Rd2 c5 $19 {Socko,B (2629)
-Wojtaszek,R (2593) Karpacz 2008 (0-1, 57)}) 24... f4 25. exf4 Rxf4 26. c5 Qd5
{With great compensation for the pawn, due to Black's safer king and control
on the light squares.}) 13... O-O-O 14. Nb3 h5 15. gxh5 g4 16. a4 Rh6 (16...
Qg5 $5 17. a5 (17. c5 Rxh5 18. Rxh5 Qxh5 19. a5 bxa5 $5 20. Nxa5 Nxa5 21. Rxa5
Qh1 22. e4 f5 $132) 17... d6 18. axb6 axb6 19. c5 dxc5 20. dxc5 Rxh5 21. Rxh5
Qxh5 $11) 17. a5 Rdh8 18. axb6 axb6 19. c5 Rxh5 20. Rxh5 Rxh5 21. cxb6 cxb6 22.
Qb2 g3 {By now it is clear that Black has very good counterplay.} 23. f3 Qg5
24. f4 (24. Kd2 Rh1 $11) 24... Qf5 25. Nd2 Rh1 26. O-O-O Kc7 27. Nc4 b5 28. Na3
Na7 29. Qd2 $2 (29. Qb4 $1 Qe4 30. Qc5+ Kb8 31. Nxb5 Nxb5 32. Bxb5 Qxe3+ 33.
Kb2 $11 {White will deliver perpetual check.}) 29... Be4 30. Kb2 Qd5 31. Rc1
Qb7 32. Ka2 Kd8 33. Qb2 Rh2 $19 {Postny,E (2424) -Marin,M (2555) Tel Aviv 2000
(0-1, 40)} *

