-7,-7,-62,-37,-37,-43,-57,7,0,93,-332,-349,-694,-716,-1886,-29986,-29987,
-29988,-29989,-29990,-29997,-29998,-29999,-30000]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3
Bb4 4. Nf3 b6 5. Bg5 Bb7 6. e3 h6 7. Bh4 g5 8. Bg3 Ne4 9. Qc2 Bxc3+ 10. bxc3
Nxg3 11. fxg3 $5 {An interesting move, aiming at depriving Black of his attack
based on advancing the h-pawn and clearing the f-file for White's major pieces.
} g4 12. Nh4 {This is the crucial idea. Apparently, the knight will be
arrested forever on h4, but the point is that after the rooks' doubling on the
f-file, Black will experience some problems. For instance, ...e6-e5 frees the
knight and ...f7-f5 makes Ng6 possible in the long run.} (12. Nd2 {offers
Black simple play.} Qg5 13. Qd3 Nc6 14. e4 h5 $15) 12... Nc6 ({The main line
goes} 12... Qg5 {, forcing the queen to go to d2 instead of e2.} 13. Qd2 Nc6
14. Bd3 f5 15. O-O {While aesthetically this looks fine for Black, I am
worried that he cannot display any active plan. White can play Rf4 and Raf1,
followed by e3-e4, and the knight will eventually emerge into play. White's
king is also safer than Black's.}) 13. Bd3 Qf6 {I have analysed this almost
untested idea a long time ago and found no reason to deviate from it when
writing this article. Black intends to cause White some loss of time when
transferring the king to g1.} 14. Qe2 {The queen occupies the optimal square
with gain of time.} (14. Rf1 Qg5 15. Rf4 f5 16. Kf1 O-O-O {offers Black an
extra tempo compared to the mainline mentioned above.} 17. Kg1 (17. Qe2 Ne7 18.
Kg1 d6 19. Raf1 Kb8 20. R4f2 {Parrying ...e6-e5.} Rhe8 21. e4 fxe4 22. Bxe4 d5
23. cxd5 Nxd5 $15 {With perfect centralisation for Black.}) 17... e5 $1 18.
dxe5 (18. Rxf5 Qxe3+) 18... Nxe5 19. Bxf5 (19. Nxf5 Rhe8 20. Be2 h5 $15 {
[%cal Ge5g6] Threatening ...Ng6.}) 19... Qe7 $11 {Due to his far better
structure, Black has full compensation for the pawn.}) 14... h5 15. Rf1 {
Preparing the king's evacuation.} (15. Rb1 {Vaganian,R (2630)-Timman,J (2610)
London 1984 (0-1, 47)} d6 {makes no real difference with respect to the main
lines.}) (15. e4 {weakens the d4-square.} d6 16. Rf1 Qg7 17. Kf2 Na5 18. Kg1 c5
19. Qf2 (19. d5 O-O-O $11) (19. e5 $2 dxe5 20. dxe5 O-O-O 21. Rf6 Rd7 22. Raf1
Rhd8 $19 {Black has the better structure and the knight on h4 is passive.
White now tried the only practical yet insufficient chance.} 23. Nf5 exf5 24.
Bxf5 {Kotronias,V (2355)-Nikolic,P (2570) Thessaloniki 1984 (0-1, 35)} Kb8 25.
Bxd7 Rxd7 26. e6 fxe6 27. Qe5+ Rc7 28. Rf8+ Bc8 $19) 19... Nc6 (19... Ba6 $5) (
19... Rf8 $5) 20. e5 O-O-O $11) (15. a4 {does not prevent Black's main plan.}
Rh6 16. Rb1 d6 17. Be4 O-O-O 18. Bxc6 Bxc6 19. a5 {Campos Moreno,J (2445)
-Marin,M (2545) Andorra 1997 (1/2-1/2, 61)} Be4 20. Ra1 Kb8 21. Rf1 Qe7 $15 {
The black king is safe and the knight is completely dominated.}) 15... Qg5 $1
$146 {This is an important improvement over my old analysis. The queen is more
active on g5 than on g7, but I probably feared it would also be exposed.} (
15... Qg7 16. Kf2 Rh6 17. Kg1 Rf6 18. Rfb1 d6 19. Be4 O-O-O 20. a4 d5 21. Bd3
Qg5 22. c5 {With unclear play in Florean,A (2450)-Marin,M (2530) Bucharest
1998 (1-0, 41)} Na5) 16. Kf2 Rh6 $1 {This is the core of Black's plan. He uses
the available time to reduce White's potential pressure along the f-file.} (
16... f5 17. Kg1 {is no improvement over the mainline mentioned above.}) 17.
Kg1 Rf6 18. Rfb1 (18. Rxf6 Qxf6 {makes Black's life simpler.} 19. Rf1 Qg7 20.
Qf2 Ba6 21. Qf4 O-O-O $5 22. Qxf7 Qxf7 23. Rxf7 Na5 $11 {White's rook is
active, but his pawns are vulnerable.}) 18... d6 19. Rb5 {If played one move
later, this would be ineffective.} (19. e4 Na5 20. Rb5 c5 21. e5 dxe5 22. dxc5
a6 $3 23. Rb2 (23. Rxb6 $2 e4 $1 $19) 23... e4 24. Bxe4 Qxc5+ 25. Kh1 O-O-O 26.
Rab1 Rd6 $17 {Black has a huge structural advantage and the knight is held
captive on h4.}) (19. a4 Na5 {is no improvement for White.}) 19... Qh6 20. e4 (
20. a4 O-O-O 21. Be4 a6 22. Rb2 Na5 23. Bxb7+ Kxb7 24. c5 dxc5 25. dxc5 Qg5 26.
cxb6 cxb6 27. Rab1 Rd6 28. e4 Qc5+ 29. Kh1 Nc4 $19 {With complete domination.})
20... O-O-O 21. a4 (21. e5 $6 {just weakens the centre.} dxe5 22. dxe5 a6 23.
exf6 (23. Rb2 Nxe5 $19) 23... axb5 24. cxb5 Ne5 $1 $19) 21... a6 22. Rb2 {
This looks logical but offers Black a choice between two promising
continuations.} ({Objectively,} 22. Rbb1 {does not make a big difference,
