7. O-O {With certain compensation for the pawn.}) 5. Bg2 (5. Bd2 {neglects the
kingside development, allowing} d5 {under improved circumstances.} 6. Bg2 (6.
cxd5 exd5 {leads to a structure which is similar to that in the Exchange
Queen's gambit, with the difference that the bishop will be misplaced on g2.}
7. Bg2 c6 8. Nf3 Re8 9. O-O Nbd7 10. a3 Bf8 {Squella Lavin,C (2136) -Vazquez,G
(2330) Asuncion 2014 (0-1, 34). Black has comfortable play, as the typical
b2-b4 weakens the square c4.}) (6. Qb3 {does not do much for the kingside
development either.} c5 7. dxc5 Nc6 8. cxd5 exd5 $15 {Soon followed by ...
d5-d4.}) 6... dxc4 7. Nf3 Nc6 8. e3 Re8 9. O-O e5 {Black does not have any
problem and he even is a pawn up for the moment. Boyd,J (1898)-Turoczi,P (1817)
LSS email 2009 (0-1, 23)}) 5... Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 d6 {Black has finally deviated
from the Catalan patterns. The bishop may stand beautifully on g2, but the
pawn on c4 is weaker than in other systems with this structure.} 7. Nf3 (7. e4
e5 8. Ne2 {is too time-consuming.} Re8 (8... b6 9. O-O Ba6 {is also possible,
taking advantage of the fact that the knight is far away from c4.}) 9. Qc2 c5
10. O-O Nc6 11. f4 {Principled but unsound.} (11. d5 Na5 12. Qd3 b6 {,
followed by ...Ba6, dooms the pawn on c4.}) (11. h3 b6 {does not change much.})
11... exd4 12. cxd4 cxd4 13. Qd3 (13. Rd1 Qb6 $17) 13... Nb4 14. Qd2 Qb6 15.
Qxd4 Nxe4 16. Bb2 Nc2 17. Qxb6 axb6 $19 {Lampert,J (2544)-Sunilduth Lyna,N 
(2575) chess.com INT 2019 (0-1, 37)}) (7. Bg5 e5 {may transpose below.}) 7...
Nc6 {The most active way of preparing ...e6-e5. Besides, the knight also steps
closer to the pawn on c4.} (7... Nbd7 {is also possible, but puts less
pressure on the centre.} 8. O-O e5 (8... Rb8 9. Re1 b6 10. e4 Bb7 11. Nh4 {
offers White a certain initiative.}) 9. Qc2 (9. c5 Re8 $5 $146 10. cxd6 cxd6
11. c4 e4 12. Nd2 d5 13. Qb3 h5 $11) 9... Qe7 10. Nh4 (10. e4 $5 {looks more
active.}) 10... Qe6 11. c5 (11. d5 Qe8 {is comfortable for Black.}) 11... d5
$11 {With a stable, even though (for the moment) a bit passive position for
Black.}) 8. Qd3 {In this line we will examine White's attempts to reach
activity by delaying castling.} (8. Ba3 Re8 {Unpins the d-pawn.} 9. O-O e5 10.
dxe5 dxe5 11. Qb3 Na5 12. Qb4 c5 $5 (12... b6 {is simpler.} 13. Nxe5 c5 14. Qb2
{Defending e2.} Bb7 15. Bxb7 Nxb7 16. Nd3 Na5 $17 {The pawn on c4 is doomed
and the bishop on a3 looks awful.}) 13. Qxc5 b6 14. Qb4 Bb7 15. Rfd1 Qc7 16. c5
Nd5 17. Qb2 e4 $5 (17... Nc4 18. Qb3 Na5 19. Qc2 Nc4 20. Qb3 Na5 21. Qc2 Nc4
22. Qb3 Na5 {1/2-1/2 Jianu,V (2532)-Banzea,A (2325) Olanesti 2018}) 18. Nd4
bxc5 19. Nb5 Qb6 $15 {With active play.}) (8. d5 {just helps Black to reach a
