1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 {This ambitious system was famously used
by the Romanian grandmaster Florin Gheorghiu to beat Robert Fischer. I have
been seduced by it in the early '90s and obtained a series of beautiful wins
with it. However, the system is a bit too provocative, as it delays White's
piece development.} c5 {In connection with the next move, one of Black's most
dynamic reactions, aiming at exploiting White's delay in development.} 5. d5 (
5. a3 {is examined in Chapter 16}) 5... b5 $5 {In the spirit of the Volga/
Benko or rather the Budapest gambits.} 6. e4 {White should not keep toying
with his development.} (6. cxb5 $2 Nxd5 $17) (6. dxe6 fxe6 7. cxb5 d5 {offers
Black a strong initiative in the centre.} 8. e3 (8. a3 Ba5 9. Bd2 O-O (9... d4
10. Na4 Nd5 11. Nxc5 Ne3 {also favours Black.}) 10. Nh3 {Brinck Claussen,B 
(2380) -Hansen,C Tarnby 1983 (1/2-1/2, 32)} c4 11. e3 (11. b4 cxb3 12. Qxb3 d4
$15) 11... Nbd7 12. Be2 Nc5 $15 {With almost complete control for Black.}) 8...
O-O 9. Bd2 {Agdestein,S (2600)-Hansen,L (2500) Novi Sad 1990 (1/2-1/2, 18)} (9.
Nge2 a6 10. bxa6 Nc6 {also yields Black a strong initiative.}) 9... d4 10. exd4
cxd4 11. Ne4 Bxd2+ 12. Nxd2 Nbd7 13. Bc4 Nb6 14. Rc1 Nfd5 15. Bxd5 Nxd5 16. Nc4
a6 {Due to the weakness on e3 and his delay in development, White's position
looks very dangerous.}) 6... d6 $1 {At this height, Black should maintain the
tension, renewing the pawn sacrifice.} (6... bxc4 7. Bxc4 {would just help
White's development.}) 7. dxe6 {This is more playable now than one move
earlier, but it does not promise an advantage at all.} (7. Bd3 {accepts
wasting a tempo after the capture on c4.} O-O 8. Nge2 (8. Bd2 exd5 9. Nxd5 Nxd5
10. cxd5 Na6 {yields Black the initiative, as} 11. Bxb5 {is risky:} Rb8 12. Bc4
Qg5 $1) 8... bxc4 9. Bxc4 exd5 10. Bxd5 (10. exd5 Nbd7 {turns d5 into a
weakness.}) 10... Nxd5 11. Qxd5 {White has managed to maintain piece control
over d5 and even wins material. However, this does not offer him any joy.} Be6
$1 12. Qxa8 Qb6 13. O-O Nc6 14. Qxf8+ Kxf8 {Due to Black's piece activity and
the asymmetric structure, the queen is stronger than the two rooks.} 15. Nf4
Bxc3 16. bxc3 Bc4 17. Rd1 Ne5 $15 18. Bd2 Qb2 {1/2-1/2 Loeffler,W (2365)-Doric,
N (2388) ICCF email 2017}) (7. Bg5 {keeps neglecting the kingside development.}
h6 8. Bh4 O-O 9. Bd3 exd5 10. cxd5 c4 11. Bc2 Bc5 {Suddenly it is not that
simple to get castled.} 12. Nge2 (12. Nxb5 Qb6 $19 {[%csl Gb5,Gg1] wins one of
the attacked knights.}) 12... b4 13. Na4 Be3 $15) (7. cxb5 exd5 8. exd5 O-O 9.
Bc4 Nh5 10. g3 Qf6 {, with a monstrous initiative for the pawn.Mann,G (2230)
-Plochl,C Stockerau 1992 (1/2-1/2, 18)}) ({For} 7. Nge2 {, see Chapter 14}) (7.
Bd2 {is examined in Chapter 15.}) 7... Bxe6 {After ...d7-d6, the plan based on
... fxe6 and ...d5 is less convincing, but Black does well using the newly
cleared c8-e6 diagonal to develop the bishop.} 8. Bf4 (8. cxb5 d5 {offers
Black adequate compensation in the centre.} 9. exd5 Nxd5 10. Kf2 (10. Bd2 O-O
11. Nxd5 Bxd5 12. Bxb4 {Bures,J (2387)-Roubalik,J (2400) Czech Republic 2017 
(1/2-1/2, 49)} Qh4+ 13. g3 Qxb4+ 14. Qd2 Re8+ 15. Be2 Nd7 $15) 10... Nxc3 11.
Qxd8+ Kxd8 12. bxc3 Bxc3 13. Bg5+ Kc7 14. Rc1 Bd4+ 15. Ke1 Nd7 16. Ne2 Be5 {
With comfortable play for Black. White has a beautiful queenside majority, but
Black's king is safer and his pieces are more active. Agaltsov,I (2428)
-Semmler,R (2362) ICCF email 2018 (1/2-1/2, 26)}) 8... O-O 9. Bxd6 (9. Nge2
Bxc4 10. Qxd6 Nbd7 11. Ng3 Nb6 $11 {Noble,M (2465) -Moll,R (2578) ICCF email
2017 (1/2-1/2, 22)}) (9. Qxd6 Qa5 10. Nge2 Bxc4 {White's delay in development
is no less relevant than his control of the centre. At this height, he has to
be careful.} 11. a3 Na6 12. Bg5 Bxe2 13. Bxf6 gxf6 14. Bxe2 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3
Qxc3+ 16. Kf2 Rad8 17. Qxa6 Qd4+ 18. Kg3 Rd6 19. Qxb5 f5 $11 {Black delivers a
perpetual.} 20. Rad1 f4+ 21. Kxf4 Rf6+ 22. Kg3 Rg6+ 23. Kh3 Rh6+ 24. Kg3 Rg6+
25. Kh3 {1/2-1/2 Caron,S (2186)-Andersen,J (2201) ICCF email 2018}) 9... Re8
10. cxb5 (10. Nge2 Bxc4 {offers Black very active play.} 11. a3 Ba5 12. Bxc5
Nbd7 13. Bd4 Qc7 14. b4 Bb6 15. Rc1 Qb7 16. Nf4 (16. Bxb6 Nxb6 17. Kf2 Rad8 {
puts White under a lot of pressure.}) 16... Nxe4 $1 {With such a huge advance
in development, a natural sacrifice.} 17. fxe4 Rxe4+ 18. Nxe4 Qxe4+ 19. Ne2 Ne5
20. Bxe5 Qxe5 21. Qc2 Qe3 22. Qf5 Re8 23. Rc2 Bd3 24. Qc8 Bxc2 25. Qxc2 Rd8 {
0-1 Liu,Z (2163)-Wang,S (2203) Hangzhou 2018}) 10... Nd5 $5 (10... Qb6 11. Bg3
a6 12. bxa6 Nxa6 $15 {also offers Black active play for the pawns.}) 11. exd5
Bf5+ 12. Kf2 (12. Nge2 Qxd6 13. g4 Bg6 14. Bg2 c4 15. O-O Bd3 16. Re1 Nd7 $17 {
With full domination. Stefan,M-Grove,A ICCF email 2017 (0-1, 16)}) 12... Qxd6
13. h4 Qf6 14. Qd2 Nd7 15. Rd1 c4 16. g4 Bc5+ 17. Kg2 Be3 18. Qe1 Bxg1 19. Qg3
Be3 20. gxf5 Qxf5 21. Bxc4 Qc2+ 22. Kh3 Nf6 $17 {0-1 (32) Adelseck,H (2396)
-Schmidt,T (2400) GER email 2017} *

