1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. f3 c5 5. d5 b5 6. e4 d6 7. Nge2 {White
intends to continue with Ng3, avoiding to waste a tempo with the bishop on its
way to c4 and hoping that Black will soon finish his neutral, half-waiting
moves. However, there is a simple answer.} bxc4 8. Nf4 {The knight has to
change its initially planned trajectory to maintain the possibility to
recapture on d5 with pieces.} (8. Ng3 exd5 9. exd5 {turns e5 into a chronic
weakness.} O-O 10. Bxc4 Re8+ 11. Be2 (11. Kf2 Nbd7 12. Bg5 h6 13. Bxf6 Nxf6 $19
{is just hopeless for White. Vakulenko,A (2306)-Ben Ari,Y (2365) Lichess.org
INT 2020 (0-1, 24)}) 11... Ba6 $5 {The weakness on d5 is there to stay.} (11...
Bb7 12. O-O Bxc3 13. bxc3 Nxd5 14. Qb3 {may offer White some light
compensation.}) 12. O-O Bxc3 13. bxc3 Bxe2 14. Nxe2 Nbd7 $17 {White has
weaknesses all over the board and is a bit behind in development.}) 8... e5 {
The natural reaction, causing White to waste more tempi on knight jumps.} 9.
Nfe2 Nbd7 10. Ng3 Nb6 11. Be2 {Black has kept his extra pawn, but for the time
being this is not so relevant. The structure is blocked and the main thing is
to find a proper plan to achieve counterplay.} Ng8 $5 {Preparing ...Ne7 and ...
f7-f5.} (11... O-O 12. O-O {leaves Black solid but a bit rigid, as the knight
on b6 has to remain immobile.}) 12. h4 {An aggressive plan.} (12. Qc2 {
Prepares a long regrouping, but gives Black the time to do the same.} Ne7 13.
O-O O-O 14. a4 Ba5 (14... a5 $5 {is not without a point. True, the bishop may
remain immobile for a long time, but it is not easy to exploit this with White.
} 15. Nb5 {allows} Ba6 {With the bishop on a5, this would not create any
threat.} 16. Na3 Qd7 17. Nxc4 Bxc4 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. Qxc4 f5 $11) 15. Nb5 Ng6 (
15... Ba6) 16. Na3 (16. Kh1 Nf4 17. Bxc4 Nxc4 18. Qxc4 Qf6 19. Ne2 Ng6 $11 {
1/2-1/2 Sarakenidis,N (2327)-Jørgensen,B (2343) ICCF email 2017}) 16... Nh4
17. Nxc4 Nxc4 18. Bxc4 f5 19. exf5 Nxf5 20. Bd3 Qf6 21. Ne4 Qe7 22. Bg5 Qf7 $11
{With normal play for Black. Van Vugt,W (2275)-Muniz Pardino,A (2381) ICCF
email 2018 (1/2-1/2, 31)}) (12. f4 {is premature, as Black can take control
over the e5-square with gain of time.} exf4 13. Bxf4 Ne7 14. O-O Ng6 15. Qc1
Bxc3 16. bxc3 O-O $11) 12... f5 (12... Ne7 13. h5 {restricts the knight, and if
} h6 14. f4 {, as ...Ng6 is not possible anymore.}) (12... h6 $5 {is
interesting, though, trying to prove that h2-h4 was rather committal.} 13. h5
Nf6 14. O-O O-O 15. f4 {White does not have any other active plan.} Bd7 {
Preventing Nb5 and getting ready for ...exf4. White is caught in his own trap,
as he cannot release the tension under favourable circumstances.} 16. fxe5 (16.
f5 Bxc3 17. bxc3 Nh7 {ensures Black absolute kingside stability, while on the
other wing he is still a pawn up.}) 16... dxe5 17. Qc2 Ne8 $15 {Followed by ...
Nd6, with a perfect blockade. I believe that this would be the line I would
try in a practical game.}) (12... Nf6 13. h5 h6 {is another possible
move-order.}) 13. exf5 (13. f4 {leads to entertaining play in the centre.}
Bxc3+ 14. bxc3 Nf6 15. O-O O-O 16. fxe5 dxe5 17. exf5 (17. Nxf5 Nxe4 $15) 17...
Qxd5 (17... Bb7 18. d6 Bd5 19. a4 a5 $11 {leaves Black very stable.}) 18. Bf3
Qxd1 19. Rxd1 Rb8 20. Bg5 Na4 21. Rac1 e4 22. Nxe4 Nxe4 23. Bxe4 Bb7 24. Bd5+
Bxd5 25. Rxd5 {Despite White's attempts to maintain the initiative, Black's
queenside activity ensures him a draw.} h5 (25... Rb2 $11) 26. Be7 Rf7 27. Bxc5
Nxc5 28. Rxc5 Rb2 29. Re1 Rxa2 30. Re8+ Kh7 31. Ree5 {1/2-1/2 Oreopoulos,K 
(2491)-Mende,I (2440) ICCF email 2018}) 13... Nf6 {Attacking d5 and thus
putting the b6-knight to work, too.} 14. Bg5 Bxc3+ 15. bxc3 O-O 16. Qd2 $5 {
There are good reasons to delay castling.} (16. O-O h6 17. Bxf6 Qxf6 18. Ne4
Qxh4 19. g4 Bb7 {is unclear.}) 16... h6 17. a4 {With the rook still on h1,
White can ignore the threat against the bishop for a while.} a5 18. Ne4 (18.
Kf2 Qc7 {Unpinning the knight.} 19. Bxf6 Rxf6 {faces Black with less problems.}
) 18... Bxf5 19. Nxf6+ Rxf6 $1 20. Bxf6 Qxf6 {Black has a pawn for the
exchange, the better structure, and the white king has problems finding safety.
} 21. Qb2 (21. h5 Re8 {Planning ... e5-e4.} 22. O-O Qh4 23. f4 e4 24. Qe1 Qf6
25. g4 $6 Bd7 $15) 21... Nd7 22. Bxc4 e4 $1 23. f4 (23. O-O exf3 24. Rxf3 Ne5
$15 {retrieves the exchange, for instance} 25. Rf4 g5 $17) 23... Nb6 $1 24. Be2
(24. Qxb6 $2 Qxc3+ 25. Kf2 {Black does not even have to take the bishop, as
his attack is strong enough.} e3+ 26. Kf3 e2+ 27. Kf2 Qd4+ 28. Kg3 Qe3+ 29. Kh2
Qxf4+ 30. Kg1 Qd4+ 31. Kh2 Qxh4+ 32. Kg1 e1=Q+) 24... Nxd5 25. Bc4 Be6 {
Due to White's incoherent structure, Black is not worse at all.} *

