19. g4 $18) 19. Be4 Re8 20. Rxh1 Rxh1+ 21. Kc2 Bxc4 22. Qxd6 Nf6 23. Qxc5 {
White's queen is very strong.}) 8. a4 {The most ambitious move, inducing Black
to clear matters on the queenside.} (8. a3 Ba5 9. a4 {allows Black to use the
b4-square:} exd5 10. cxd5 b4 11. Nb1 O-O 12. Bg5 Nbd7 13. Nd2 (13. b3 Qe8 14.
Nd2 Bd8 15. Ne2 {This knight cannot get involved in the fight for the
c4-square, unfortunately.} Ne5 16. Qb1 Nh5 17. Bxd8 Qxd8 {, followed by ...
f7-f5, soon leaves White underdeveloped.}) 13... b3 $1 {The key to Black's
counterplay.} 14. Qxb3 h6 15. Bf4 (15. Bh4 Bxd2+ 16. Kxd2 Nxe4+ $19) 15... Rb8
16. Qc2 Nxd5 $1 17. exd5 Qf6 {Threatening ...Rxb2.} 18. O-O-O (18. Be3 Rxb2 19.
Qc1 {Otherwise at least ...Rxd2.} Re8 $19) 18... Qxf4 19. Ne2 Qb4 20. Nc3 Nb6
21. Re1 c4 22. g4 Bd7 23. Re4 Rfc8 {0-1 Mamedyarov,S (2764)-Rapport,R (2747)
Saint Louis 2019}) (8. Nge2 {looks like a slow way of developing.} O-O 9. Nf4 (
9. Ng3 Nbd7 10. dxe6 fxe6 11. cxb5 d5 12. exd5 exd5 13. Be2 c4 14. O-O Kh8 $146
{[%cal Gd5d4] The best way to prepare the crushing ...d5-d4, as the c4-pawn is
not hanging with check anymore.} 15. Be3 Bc5 16. Bxc5 Nxc5 17. b4 Ne6 $17 {
The central pawns are unstoppable.}) 9... exd5 10. Ncxd5 (10. cxd5 {leads to
some sort of Benoni in which the knight is not especially well-placed on f4.
The point is that the Black knight will enjoy stability on e5.} Nbd7 11. Be2
Ne5 12. O-O c4 13. g4 Nfd7 14. Kh1 Ba5 15. Qe1 Nc5 16. Qg3 {Midoux,S (2288)
-Inkiov,V (2440) Paris 2002 (0-1, 45)} Ncd3 {With active play.}) 10... Nxd5 11.
Nxd5 Bxd2+ 12. Qxd2 Nc6 $11 {The d4-square is no less important than the one
on d5.} 13. cxb5 $6 Nd4 14. bxa6 Qh4+ 15. Kd1 Bxa6 16. Qf4 Qd8 17. Qe3 Kh8 18.
Qc3 Bb7 19. Bc4 f5 20. exf5 Rxf5 $19 {Aronian,L (2773)-Grischuk,A (2777)
Lichess.org INT 2020 4.f3 [Mihail] (1-0, 68)}) 8... exd5 {The simplest way to
achieve counterplay based on White's delay in development.} ({The familiar} 
8... Bxc3 {remains interesting under the changed circumstances, but still
looks like a small concession.} 9. Bxc3 (9. bxc3 bxc4 10. Bxc4 exd5 11. exd5
O-O 12. Ne2 Nbd7 $15) 9... b4 10. Bd2 O-O 11. Ne2 exd5 12. exd5 (12. cxd5 Nh5)
12... Nh5 13. Qb3 f5 14. O-O-O Ra7 15. Ng3 {Garau,B (2349)-Vasconcellos,R 
(2417) ICCF email 2018 (1/2-1/2, 29)} Qh4 16. Nxh5 Qxh5 17. Re1 f4 18. Bd3 Raf7
19. Qc2 Nd7 $11 {[%cal Gd7e5,Gc8f5] , followed by ...Ne5 and ...Bf5, with a
stable position.}) 9. cxd5 bxa4 {Just a small structural concession, offering
Black active minor piece play.} 10. Qxa4+ Nbd7 11. Nge2 O-O 12. Ng3 {Abrashkin,
B (2407)-Schrik,R (2198) chess.com INT 2020 (0-1, 17)} a5 $1 $146 {
