is doomed.}) ({It is too late to return onto a normal Saemisch path, as after} 
7. e3 O-O 8. Bd3 b6 9. Ne2 {the bishop is able to go directly to a6, while
White has lost a tempo with f2-f3 anyway.} Ba6 10. O-O Ne8 11. e4 Na5 $17 {
Compare with the Saemisch attack line.}) (7. dxc5 Qa5 {retrieves the pawn,
winning a tempo over the variation above.}) 7... d6 {White's problem is that
due to the hanging d4-pawn he cannot develop naturally with Bd3 and Ne2.} 8.
Be3 (8. Ne2 b6 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Na5 11. Nc1 Bd7 12. a4 (12. Bd3 e5 13. O-O g5
14. Bf2 Nh5 15. g3 Bh3 16. Re1 Rg8 17. Nb3 Nxb3 18. Qxb3 Nf4 $1 19. Bf1 Qc8 $15
) 12... e5 13. Nb3 Nxb3 14. Qxb3 g5 15. Bf2 Nh5 16. g3 O-O {Black has
displayed most of his pawns on the dark squares, restricting the White bishop.
His position is rock solid and offers chances to take over the initiative.} 17.
h4 (17. Bd3 Bh3) (17. Bg2 Ng7 18. O-O Ne6 $15) 17... g4 $15) (8. Nh3 {runs into
} e5 9. d5 Bxh3 10. dxc6 Bc8 11. cxb7 Bxb7 $15 {Bhakti,K (2281)-Ghosh,D (2570)
Mumbai 2016 (0-1, 47)}) 8... b6 9. Bd3 (9. Qa4 Qd7 (9... Bd7 {is also possible,
even though the bishop moves farther from the c4-pawn.} 10. Qc2 Na5 11. Bd3 Rc8
12. Qe2 Qc7) 10. Rd1 Na5 11. Qb5 {The only chance.} (11. Qc2 Qc7 12. Nh3 Ba6
$17 {Bourmistrov,D (1893)-Kildisas,V (1822) Box Hill 2000 (0-1, 30)}) 11...
Qxb5 $5 12. cxb5 a6 13. a4 c4 {Even though White does not have doubled pawns
anymore, his light squares remain weak and his development rather poor.}) (9.
d5 Na5 $15) 9... Na5 10. Nh3 {Leaving the e2-square available for the queen,
to defend c4.} (10. Ne2 Ba6 11. Ng3 Qc7 {Preparing to get castled without
allowing the pin with Bg5.} 12. O-O O-O 13. dxc5 (13. Bg5 Ne8) 13... dxc5 14.
Qe2 Rad8 15. Rfd1 h6 16. Nf1 Nh5 17. g3 f5 $17 {Huzita,S (2061)-Scharf,N (2069)
ICCF email 2012 (0-1, 26)}) (10. f4 Bb7 $1 $146 {Causing unexpected problems
in the centre.} (10... Ba6 11. Nf3 {offers White a certain harmony.}) 11. Qf3 (
11. d5 exd5 12. cxd5 O-O {leaves the pawn on e4 vulnerable.}) (11. e5 Bxg2 12.
exf6 Qxf6 $17) 11... O-O 12. Ne2 Rc8 13. Rc1 Ba6 {The bishop has kept the
e4-pawn under a pin until Black managed to get castled. Now is time to switch
to another diagonal.} 14. e5 Ne8 15. Qh3 g6 $15) 10... Ba6 11. Qe2 (11. O-O Qd7
{threatens ...Bxc4 and enables ...0-0-0.}) 11... Qd7 12. e5 (12. f4 cxd4 13.
cxd4 d5 14. cxd5 Bxd3 15. Qxd3 exd5 16. e5 Ne4 $15 {[%cal Gf7f5] The control
over e4 and c4 offers Black excellent play.}) (12. O-O Qa4 13. Bf4 {The only
chance to get some play.} O-O-O 14. e5 dxe5 15. Qxe5 Kb7 $1 16. Qc7+ Ka8 17.
Qxf7 Rd7 18. Qxe6 cxd4 19. cxd4 Re8 20. Qf5 Rxd4 {[%cal Ga6c8] Threatening ...
Bc8.} 21. Nf2 Bxc4 22. Bxc4 Qxc4 23. Bg5 Rd5 24. Qf4 Qxf4 25. Bxf4 Nc4 $15 {
The mass exchanges have not changed the overall evaluation. White's queenside,
in particular the a3-pawn and the light squares, remains weak.}) 12... dxe5 13.
dxe5 Ng8 14. O-O Ne7 15. Rad1 Qc7 16. Bg5 O-O-O 17. Nf2 Rd7 18. Bxe7 Rxe7 19.
f4 {Spassky,B (2625)-Huebner,R (2620) Bugojno 1982 (1/2-1/2, 63)} f5 20. exf6
gxf6 $15 {White does not have anything to show for the permanent weakness on
c4.} *

