{[%evp 0,52,18,20,16,-5,-5,1,25,-2,-3,-14,1,13,23,16,19,27,24,39,33,28,51,54,
76,-14,21,-31,51,17,-14,-5,-24,-65,-92,-92,-68,-92,-82,-58,-26,-122,-107,-55,
-121,-120,-105,-105,-125,-151,-131,-141,-132,-182,-179]} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3.
Nc3 Bb4 4. a3 {The Saemisch attack is the most straightforward attempt to
question the viability of Black's opening. White builds a massive pawn centre,
intending to launch a kingside attack. Practice has shown that the weakness on
c4 and the tempo wasted on the last move offer Black excellent counterplay,
though.} ({Often White delays a2-a3 by playing} 4. e3 b6 ({It has been known
for a long time that} 4... d5 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 O-O 7. cxd5 exd5 8. Bd3 {
offers White chances to put his centre in motion, with serious effects on
Black's kingside safety.}) (4... O-O {is more flexible:} 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5
{, transposing below.}) 5. a3 Bxc3+ 6. bxc3 c5 7. Bd3 Bb7 8. f3 Nc6 {Once
again transposing.}) 4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 c5 6. e3 {At this height, White
focuses on quick piece development.} (6. f3 {is not without drawbacks, see
Line 38.}) 6... b6 7. Bd3 Bb7 {Black has two different move-orders at his
disposal. At first sight, it might seem that the last move implies the loss of
a tempo, as the bishop belongs to a6. However, this is not true, if we
consider that White's main plan is based on placing his pawns on e4 and f4.
With our main move order, he will also have to waste a tempo on f3-f4.} ({
I will highlight some minor differences arising after} 7... Nc6 {to explain my
mainline choice.} 8. Ne2 O-O 9. e4 Ne8 10. Be3 (10. O-O Ba6 11. f4 {just
transposes to the mainline.}) 10... Ba6 11. Ng3 (11. Qa4 {is similar to the
line starting with 11.Be3 below. The only difference is that in that case,
White has f2-f3 on the board, an extra tempo which looks more like a weakening.
}) 11... Na5 12. Qe2 Rc8 13. d5 Qh4 ({With the pawn on f3, this setup is not
viable due to} 13... Nd6 $6 {, winning the pawn on c4 without compensation,
but here this reaction is not recommendable:} 14. e5 Ndxc4 15. Qh5 {This is
the point. White has a dangerous attack.}) 14. O-O Nd6 15. e5 Ndxc4 16. Bc1 $5
{White retains certain attacking chances.}) 8. f3 (8. Nf3 {does not suit the
Saemisch spirit, as the knight blocks the path for the f-pawn. In fact, by
having played a2-a3, Black gave up a tempo over a variation of the Rubinstein
system.} O-O 9. O-O d6 10. Re1 (10. Nd2 Nc6 11. f4 {weakens e3 and e4,
allowing Black to change plans:} Ba6 $146 12. Qe2 d5 13. cxd5 Bxd3 14. Qxd3
exd5 $15) (10. Qe2 Be4 {exchanges the bishops, reducing White's attacking
chances and leaving him with the chronic weakness on c4.}) (10. Qc2 {allows
the familiar} Bxf3 11. gxf3 Nc6 12. Kh1 e5 13. Rg1 Ne7 $146 14. Bd2 Kh8 15. Rg5
Ng6 16. Rag1 Qe7 {[%cal Ga8e8] , planning ...Rae8, with a flexible position
and certain perspectives to break in the centre.} 17. h4 $2 {is unsound.} Nxh4
18. Rxg7 Nxf3 19. R1g2 e4 $19) 10... Ne4 $1 {A good reaction with the rook on
e1, as White does not have Ne1 followed by f2-f3 anymore. We had something
similar in Line 10, after 9.Re1.} 11. Qc2 f5 $15 12. Nd2 $2 Nxf2 $1 $146 {
A paradoxical winning sacrifice. Black's queenside is incompletely developed
and yet he starts a resolute attack. The explanation is that White's queenside
is very passive and his central pieces create some sort of barrier, preventing
the king from reaching safety.} 13. Kxf2 Qh4+ 14. Kf1 e5 $3 (14... Qxh2 15. Nf3
$16) 15. Nf3 (15. Bxf5 e4 $19) 15... Bxf3 16. gxf3 e4 17. Be2 Rf6 18. Bd1 Rg6
19. Re2 Qh3+ 20. Ke1 Rg1+ 21. Kd2 exf3 22. Rf2 Qh4 23. Rxf3 (23. Kd3 Rxd1+ 24.
Qxd1 Qxf2) 23... Qe1+ 24. Kd3 Qxd1+) 8... Nc6 9. Ne2 (9. e4 {gives up a pawn
without adequate compensation.} cxd4 10. cxd4 Nxd4 11. Bb2 Nc6 12. Nh3 Qc7 13.
f4 Na5 14. Qe2 Nb3 15. Rd1 Nc5 16. e5 Nfe4 17. O-O h6 18. Bb1 O-O-O $17 {
Balanel,I-Olafsson,F Marianske Lazne/ Prague 1954 (0-1, 48)}) 9... O-O 10. e4 (
10. O-O Na5 11. e4 {makes no difference.}) 10... Ne8 $1 {An important move in
Black's setup. The knight avoids the unpleasant pin created by Bg5 and is
prepared to jump to d6, increasing the pressure on c4.} 11. O-O (11. Be3 {
is an important alternative.} Ba6 12. Qa4 {White tries to question Black's
queenside stability.} (12. dxc5 Ne5 13. cxb6 axb6 14. Bd4 Nxc4 $15 {Black has
the better structure and White's pieces are rather restrained.}) (12. Ng3 Na5
13. Qe2 Rc8 14. Rc1 Nd6 {dooms the pawn on c4.} 15. e5 Ndxc4 16. Ne4 cxd4 17.
Bxd4 Bb7 $17 18. f4 $6 Bxe4 19. Qxe4 Qh4+ 20. g3 Qh3 21. Bf1 Qh6 22. h4 d5 $19
{Potula,K (2042)-Ruiz Castillo,J (2371) Dallas 2016 (0-1, 26)}) 12... Na5 13.
dxc5 (13. O-O Nd6 14. dxc5 Ndxc4 $15) 13... d6 14. cxb6 (14. cxd6 Nxd6 $17 {
retrieves the pawn on c4 soon, with a huge structural advantage.}) (14. c6 e5 {
Restricting the knight.} 15. Nc1 {Hurrying to defend c6.} Nc7 16. Na2 Ne6 17.
Nb4 Bxc4 18. Bxc4 Nxc4 19. Nd5 (19. Bf2 Qg5 20. O-O Nd2) 19... Nxe3 20. Nxe3
Nc5 21. Qb5 a6 22. Qe2 Rc8 $17 {The pawn on c6 is doomed.}) 14... axb6 15. Kf2
(15. Rb1 Qc8 16. Rb4 Nc6 17. Rxb6 Ne5 $17) 15... Qc8 16. Rhb1 Bxc4 17. Qc2 {
Szabo,L-Zuidema,C Amsterdam 1965 (1-0, 39)} Nf6 18. Bxb6 (18. Rxb6 d5 19. exd5
Nxd5 20. Bxh7+ Kh8 21. Bd4 Qd8 $19 {The rook is attacked and the bishop is
hanging to ...Qh4.}) 18... Qa6 $15) 11... Na5 12. Ng3 {Preparing f3-f4.} (12.
f4 {is comfortably met with} f5 13. e5 d6 {White's minor pieces are passive
and his structure is weak.} 14. Be3 Ba6 15. Qa4 Rc8 16. Rac1 cxd4 17. cxd4 d5
$17) ({If} 12. Be3 {, Black can ignore the threat on c5:} Nd6 13. dxc5 Ndxc4
14. Bxc4 (14. Bf2 bxc5 15. Bxc5 Qg5 16. Bf2 Ne3 17. Bxe3 Qxe3+ 18. Kh1 d5 19.
exd5 Bxd5 $17) 14... Nxc4 15. Bf2 Qc8 16. cxb6 axb6 $17 {Drevikovsky,
V-Bennborn,J (2243) ICCF email 2000 (0-1, 39)}) (12. e5 Ba6 13. Qc2 h6 14. f4
f5 15. exf6 Rxf6 {does not offer realistic attacking chances, either, while
the pawn on c4 is as weak as ever.}) (12. d5 Nd6 13. Qe1 Ndxc4 14. Qg3 Qe7 15.
Bh6 f6 16. Rae1 Rae8 17. Bc1 Qf7 18. Qh3 Ne5 $17 {Schouwerwou,X (1978)-Merbis,
M (2094) Haarlem 2006 (0-1, 50)}) 12... Ba6 13. f4 ({White cannot defend c4
under favourable circumstances:} 13. Qe2 cxd4 14. cxd4 Nb3 15. Rb1 Nxd4 $17)
13... f6 {Slowing down White's pawn attack.} 14. f5 Bxc4 15. Bxc4 Nxc4 {
Black has fulfilled his initial program by winning the pawn on c4 and
exchanging the light-squared bishops. Practice has shown that White's
attacking chances are not that realistic.} 16. Rf4 (16. Rb1 {, preventing ...
b6-b5, wastes time.} Rc8 17. Rf4 cxd4 18. cxd4 Qc7 19. Rh4 Ncd6 $1 {White
cannot prevent ...Qc2, for instance} 20. Qh5 Qc2 $1 $19 {It appears that the
threat Qxh7+ is not that terrible.} 21. Qxh7+ Kf7 22. Ra1 Qd1+ 23. Nf1 Qxd4+) (
16. Nh5 {0-1 (36) Weser, A (2104) -Friedman,J (2207) Philadelphia 2006} cxd4
17. cxd4 Qe7 18. Qg4 Rc8) 16... cxd4 17. cxd4 (17. Rh4 dxc3 {does not offer
White compensation for the pawns. After the first wave of his attack will come
