1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 {Once a Spassky favourite, the idea of
this move is similar to 4.Nf3 b6 5.Bg5. White intends to use the bishop's
absence from e7 to provoke the kingside weakening with ... h7-h6 and ...g7-g5.
By developing the king's knight's development, he does not concede the
e4-square, but since Black has not played ...b7-b6 yet, he can switch to a
different plan.} h6 5. Bh4 c5 6. d5 {The principled answer.} (6. e3 Qa5 7. Qc2
Ne4 8. Rc1 d5 {offers Black easy play.}) (6. Nf3 {allows} g5 7. Bg3 g4 8. Ne5
Ne4 9. Qd3 Qa5 10. Rc1 Qxa2 11. Kd1 Qb3+ 12. Rc2 Bxc3 13. bxc3 Nxg3 14. hxg3
Nc6 15. Nxc6 dxc6 $15 {Salvador Marques,C (2401)-Moura,A (2432) ICCF email
2010 (1/2-1/2, 47)}) 6... Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 {Black prepares to block the centre
after having spoiled White's queenside structure.} 8. e3 {The most flexible
move.} ({White should not be in a hurry to concede the f4-square with} 8. f3 e5
9. e4 {, which also obstructs the b1-h7 diagonal.} Nbd7 10. Bd3 Nf8 11. Ne2 g5
12. Bf2 Ng6 13. g3 (13. Ng3 h5 $146 14. Qc2 Nf4 15. Bf1 h4 16. Nf5 Bxf5 17.
exf5 g4 18. O-O-O Qd7 $17) 13... Bh3 14. Rg1 Bd7 15. Qc2 Qe7 $5 $146 {
Preparing to castle long before starting active kingside operations.} 16. Rb1
O-O-O 17. Qb2 b6 18. a4 Kc7 19. a5 Rb8 $15 {There is not much happening on the
queenside, and Black will soon be able to start an active kingside plan.}) (8.
dxe6 Bxe6 9. e3 Nc6 10. Nf3 g5 11. Bg3 Ne4 $15) 8... e5 {An important tabiya
of the Leningrad system. White intends to combine the light static queenside
pressure (a2-a4-a5, Rb1) with dynamic kingside ideas (f2-f4, or after ...g7-g5,
h2-h4, the pressure along the b1-h7 diagonal). However, practice has shown
that Black can regroup at leisure.} 9. Nf3 {This apparently flexible move
offers Black active play.} (9. f3 {, planning Bd3, is best met with} e4 $1 {
, causing White concrete problems in the centre.} 10. Qc2 (10. Ne2 Nbd7 {
leaves White without constructive moves.}) (10. fxe4 g5 11. e5 gxh4 12. exf6
Qxf6 13. Qc2 Rg8 14. O-O-O Bg4 15. Re1 Nd7 $19 {Udvari,N (1720)-Huntley,T 
(1675) LSS email 2009 (1-0, 27)}) (10. f4 {runs into} g5 $1 11. fxg5 Ng4 12.
Nh3 Qe7 13. Qd2 Ne5 14. Qf2 Ng6 15. Rb1 Nd7 $17 {, followed by ...Ne5, with
serious strategic problems for White.}) 10... g5 11. Bg3 Qe7 12. f4 Ng4 $5 $146
13. Qd2 (13. Qe2 {prevents the mainline regrouping, but the queen is misplaced
on e2, as it blocks the whole kingside development.} gxf4 14. exf4 f5 15. h3
Nf6 16. Bh4 Nbd7) 13... gxf4 14. exf4 (14. Bxf4 Ne5 {causes White problems
with developing his knight.}) 14... h5 15. h3 Nh6 $15 {Planning ...Nf5
followed by . ..h5-h4.}) (9. Bd3 {is examined in Chapter 19.}) (9. Qc2 {
is the subject of Chapter 20.}) 9... Bf5 $1 {The most active move.} 10. Nd2 {
White hurries to free the bishop's escape in case of emergency.} (10. Be2 Nbd7
11. Nd2 g5 12. Bg3 h5 {, with an initiative.}) 10... g5 11. Bg3 Nbd7 12. f3 Nf8
13. e4 {The bishop is hard to tolerate, of course. White finally decides to
advance his f-pawn, but unlike in the line with 8.f3, he managed to transfer
his knight to d2. To what extent this favours him is a different question.} (
13. Bf2 e4 $15) (13. Be2 Ng6 {does not alter Black's plan.}) 13... Bd7 14. Bf2
h5 (14... Ng6 $5 {is more solid.}) 15. h4 $6 $146 (15. Be3 Rg8 16. Bd3 h4 17.
g3 g4 $1 (17... hxg3 {unnecessarily opens the h-file.} 18. hxg3 g4 19. f4 exf4
{Gabriel,C (2560) -Hjartarson,J (2640) Germany 2003 (0-1, 47)} 20. Bxf4 Qe7 21.
Qb3 b6 22. e5 dxe5 23. Be3 {, with a strong initiative.}) 18. f4 exf4 19. Bxf4
Qe7 {Planning ... Ng6-e5.} 20. Qb3 b6 21. e5 dxe5 22. Be3 Nh5 $5 $15 {With the
h-file unavailable, White does not have compensation for the pawn.}) 15... g4 (
15... gxh4 {is another interesting possibility.} 16. Bxh4 Ng6 17. Bg5 h4 {
An interesting fight for the dark squares starts now.} 18. Nb3 Ke7 $3 {
Paradoxically, the most coherent way to free himself from the pin.} 19. Qd2 b6
20. O-O-O Qf8 21. Bd3 Qg7 22. Rh2 Kd8 23. Rdh1 Kc7 24. Bxh4 (24. Kb2 Nh5 {
does not improve White's position.}) 24... Nxh4 25. Rxh4 Rxh4 26. Rxh4 Rh8 27.
Rxh8 Qxh8 28. Qf2 Qh2 29. Nd2 Nh5 {Due to his activity and control over the
dark squares, Black has good compensation for the pawn.}) 16. Be3 Rg8 17. Qb3
b6 18. a4 (18. f4 $6 g3 $1 $17 {causes White serious kingside problems.} 19.
fxe5 (19. Be2 exf4 20. Bxf4 Ng4 21. Bxd6 Qf6 22. Bxg3 Ne3 $19) 19... Ng4 $19)
18... Ng6 19. a5 gxf3 20. gxf3 Nf4 $11 {The position is statically balanced.}
21. Bxf4 exf4 22. axb6 axb6 23. Rxa8 Qxa8 24. Qxb6 Qa1+ 25. Nb1 Bg4 $5 {
An elegant way to clear the d7-square for the knight in anticipation of e4-e5.}
26. fxg4 Nd7 27. Qb3 Ke7 {The knight on b1 is in danger in view of ...Rb8.} 28.
Bd3 Rb8 29. Qd1 Ne5 30. O-O hxg4 {Black has great compensation for the piece
and White should probably think of simplifying to a draw:} 31. Rxf4 Nxd3 32.
Qxd3 Rxb1+ 33. Rf1 Rxf1+ 34. Qxf1 Qxc3 $11 *

