2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 h6 5. Bh4 c5 6. d5 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. e3 e5 9. Bd3
{White takes the b1-h7 diagonal under control, anticipating Black's ...g7-g5.}
e4 {This is far away from one-sided, as it offers more space to the other
bishop. However, the main issue is that the light-squared bishop and the
knight will be strongly restricted. Besides, Black can transfer his queen's
knight to e5 to neutralise the pressure along the h2-b8 diagonal. The only
real danger is connected with the possible positional sacrifice Ne2-d4, and if.
.. cxd4 then cxd4. However, this works only under certain circumstances,
usually if the black king is unsafe.} (9... Nbd7 10. f3 {allows White to
continue his main idea.}) 10. Bc2 (10. Bxe4 g5 {wins a piece.}) (10. Bxf6 Qxf6
11. Bxe4 Qxc3+ 12. Ke2 Qxc4+ {wins a pawn with gain of time.}) 10... Nbd7 11.
Ne2 {The natural continuation.} ({We are familiar with the fact that the
