the c4-pawn is not so easy to defend.} 12. Qe2 Bg4 13. Qf1 g5 {A familiar plan.
} 14. fxg5 Nh5 15. a4 hxg5 16. Bf2 {Ivanchuk,V (2717)-Topalov,V (2718) Wijk
aan Zee 2001 (1/2-1/2, 36)} Qf6 17. Ra3 Qe5 18. a5 Ke7 $5 {White is almost
paralysed. For instance, if} 19. h3 Ng3 $19) 11... Qe7 {Black should not hurry
with ...g7-g5.} (11... g5 12. Bg3 Qe7 {allows White to display some activity
with} 13. h4 Rg8 14. hxg5 hxg5 15. Rb1 Kd8 16. Ba4 {In principle, Black is in
no immediate danger, but the following game illustrates some of White's ideas.}
Ne5 17. Bxe5 Qxe5 18. Kd2 Kc7 19. Qb3 Rb8 20. Qb5 {Suddenly, the threat Qa5 is
not easy to meet. A good example of how effective a piece attack on a narrow
area can be.} Bd7 21. Qa5+ b6 22. Qxa7+ Rb7 23. Qa6 Bxa4 24. Qxa4 Ng4 25. Qc6+
Kb8 26. Rxb6 {1-0 Rogozenko,D-Paschall,W World Chess Network (rapid) 2001}) 12.
Qb1 {Trying to provoke a commitment from Black.} (12. Ba4 {releases the
pressure on e4 and misplaces the bishop. These are enough reasons to change
the plan and castle short:} g5 13. Bg3 O-O 14. h4 Nb6 $5 $146 ({More ambitious
than} 14... Ne5 {, which is good enough, though. In Liebowitz,E-Browne,W (2530)
New York 1985 (0-1, 31) the critical continuation was} 15. Bxe5 Qxe5 16. Qc2
Bf5 17. Ng3 Bg6 {, and Black had a comfortable position.}) 15. Bb3 Bg4 16. Qc2
Nh5 {Suddenly, White's minor pieces look very clumsy. White has to reckon with
...f7-f5-f4, among other things.} 17. O-O-O (17. Bh2 gxh4 $5) (17. hxg5 hxg5
18. Bh2 Kg7 19. O-O-O Rh8 $17) (17. Kd2 Bxe2 18. Kxe2 Nxg3+ 19. fxg3 Kg7 $19)
17... a5 18. a4 Nxg3 19. Nxg3 (19. fxg3 {is simply awful for White, as his
minor pieces do not have any mobility.}) 19... Bxd1 20. Qxd1 f5 21. hxg5 hxg5
22. Qh5 Qg7 {[%cal Gb6d7,Gd7e5] , followed by ...Nd7-e5, when White's
compensation is questionable.}) (12. O-O {offers Black a clear target:} g5 13.
Bg3 h5 14. h4 Nh7 15. Qb1 (15. hxg5 Nxg5 {, followed by ...Ne5 and ...h5-h4-h3,
is decisive.}) 15... gxh4 16. Bf4 Ng5 17. Bxg5 Qxg5 18. Nf4 Nf6 19. Kh2 h3 20.
gxh3 Bxh3 $1 21. Rg1 (21. Kxh3 Qg4+ 22. Kh2 Qh4+ 23. Kg1 Rg8+ 24. Ng2 Qg4) (21.
Nxh3 Ng4+ {also wins.} 22. Kh1 Qh4 23. Kg2 Nxe3+ 24. fxe3 Rg8+) 21... Ng4+ 22.
Kxh3 Nxf2+ 23. Kh2 Qh4+ 24. Kg2 Rg8+ {0-1 Bredenhof,B (2215)-Schaefer,U (2226)
ICCF email 2010}) 12... O-O 13. O-O (13. Ng3 g5 {wins material.} 14. Nf5 Qe5
15. Nxh6+ Kg7 $19) (13. Bxf6 Nxf6 14. Ng3 Qe5 $17) (13. a4 {Trying to give
some meaning to the rook's presence on a1.} g5 $5 $146 14. Bg3 Ne5 15. Qb3 (15.
Bxe5 Qxe5 16. Kd2 Bf5 $15 17. Qxb7 $2 Ng4 18. Raf1 Nxh2 $19) 15... Nd3+ 16.
Bxd3 exd3 17. Nc1 h5 18. h4 Ne4 $19) 13... g5 14. Bg3 Nb6 $1 $146 (14... Ne5 {
offers White some dynamic ideas, even though their final evaluation remains
unclear.} 15. Bxe5 Qxe5 16. Ng3 Re8 17. f3 exf3 18. Rxf3 Bg4 19. Rf2 Re7 20.
Bf5 Qxc3 {White may not have full compensation for the pawn, but at least his
pieces are playing.}) 15. Bb3 Nh5 {Followed by ...f7-f5. With the bishop on b3,
White does not have the same chances as in the line above.} *

