1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 Bb4 4. Bg5 h6 5. Bh4 c5 6. d5 Bxc3+ 7. bxc3 d6 8. e3
e5 9. Qc2 {White prepares to play Nf3-d2 without allowing ...Bf5.} Nbd7 10. Nf3
Qe7 11. Nd2 {One thing I was sure about when facing this position was that I
would not hurry with ...g7-g5 or ...e5-e4, which offers White ideas for early
pawn breaks with either h2-h4 or ...f2-f3.} Kd8 $5 {Since I was not going to
castle short for sure, this looks like the only way of implementing my "plan".
Engines are outraged by this move, possibly because losing the right to castle
weighs a bit too much in their system of evaluation.} (11... g5 12. Bg3 {
[%cal Gh2h4,Gf2f3]} Nh5 13. Bd3 Ndf6 14. f3 Nxg3 15. hxg3 g4 16. Bf5 Kd8 17.
Ke2 Kc7 18. Raf1 Bd7 19. fxg4 Nxg4 20. Bxd7 Qxd7 21. Qf5 f6 22. Ne4 {Berkes,F 
(2678) -Chuchelov,V (2565) Germany 2011 (1-0, 39), with slight pressure.}) 12.
Be2 (12. Bd3 {looks more active. I was surprised to find a game in which Black
played a plan similar to mine:} Kc7 13. f3 Nb6 14. a4 {This is natural, but
White will now have to live with a permanent weakness on a4.} g5 15. Bg3 (15.
Bf2 a5 16. h4 g4 {Planning ...Nh5.} 17. h5 Qe8 {Targeting a4 and soon h5.})
15... a5 16. Bf5 {If Black had a dark-squared bishop, this exchange would
cause him strategic problems. The way it is, the only bishop that could turn
"bad" is White's.} (16. h4 Nh5 17. Bf2 g4 $15) 16... Bxf5 17. Qxf5 Nh5 ({
It looks safer to clear the f-pawn's path by defending the b6-knight with} 
17... Nfd7 18. O-O h5 19. Rfb1 Qf6 20. Qc2 Rag8 21. Rb5 h4 22. Bf2 g4 $36 {
Black's initiative develops faster.}) 18. Qc2 Qd7 19. O-O f5 20. Rfb1 Nxg3 21.
hxg3 h5 22. Rb5 $2 {Missing his best chance.} (22. Qb2 $1 Ra6 23. Ra3 $18)
22... Nc8 23. Rab1 b6 $11 {Djukic,Z (2385)-Abramovic,B (2490) Kladovo 1996 (1/
2-1/2, 33). Everything is safely blocked on the queenside and it is only Black
who can hope to make progress on the kingside.}) 12... Kc7 13. Rb1 {White
gladly embarks on a semi-waiting game, hoping that Black will finish the
useful moves first.} (13. O-O-O {is quite committal, delaying White's play
along the b-file for a long while.} g5 14. Bg3 h5 15. h4 g4 16. Bd3 Nb6 17. Kb1
Bd7 18. Ka1 Raf8 19. Rb1 Ne8 20. e4 Ng7 21. f4 gxf3 22. gxf3 f5 $132 {
Marusenko,P-Levin,F (2320) Naleczow 1989 (1/2-1/2, 60)}) 13... Nb6 $5 {I
confess I did not know the aforementioned games featuring this manoeuvre, but
during my short preparation I had noticed that my engine occasionally
suggested placing the knight on b6. Over the board, I thought this would not
be such a bad idea. First of all, Black secures his queenside, but more
importantly he gets at least one more useful half-waiting move (...Bd7), while
White seems to have exhausted his.} ({My last move turned out to be a novelty
compared to an old game of my opponent, which I had witnessed personally:} 
13... g5 14. Bg3 Ne8 15. h4 Rg8 16. hxg5 hxg5 17. Bd3 (17. f3 {fails to
prevent ...f7-f5 properly:} Ng7 18. e4 f5 $5 19. exf5 Nf6 20. Bd3 Ngh5 21. Bf2
g4 $132 {Black will soon have the dream square f4 for his h5-knight.}) 17...
Ng7 18. Rh6 $6 {This only wastes time.} (18. f3 Qf8 {[%cal Gf7f5] leaves White
with nothing better than} 19. Ne4 Qe7 {[%cal Gf7f5]} 20. Nd2 {, with a
repetition.}) ({It seems to be best to keep the f3-square available for the
knight with, say,} 18. a4 {Engines claim that now 18...f5 offers entirely
adequate compensation for the pawn, but I would be afraid that in the long run
f2-f4 could turn the g3-bishop into a dangerous piece. Still, sooner or later
Black may have to sacrifice the pawn, since otherwise it will not be easy to
make progress on the kingside, while on the opposite wing, White will increase
his pressure with simple moves. For instance} Qf8 19. Nf3 $1 {The point.} Qe7
20. a5 f5 21. Bxf5 Nxf5 22. Qxf5 Nf6 23. Qc2 Bd7 $44) 18... Nf6 19. Be2 (19. f3
Ngh5 20. Bf2 Qf8 $17) 19... Nf5 20. Rh2 Bd7 21. Nf1 {1/2-1/2 Ionescu,C (2480)
-Lokotar,E (2340) Vosu 1989} Rh8 $15 {Black is perfectly regrouped and ready
to take over the initiative along the h-file.}) 14. Kd1 {My opponent played
this rather quickly and I felt it actually suits his slow manoeuvring style.
But the king's road to safety is long and this allows Black to prepare his
pawn counterplay. Now I am not sure which is the best continuation.} (14. a4 a5
{[%cal Ga8a6,Gc8d7] creates the familiar problems.}) ({On the other hand,} 14.
O-O {offers Black a clear target:} g5 15. Bg3 h5 16. h4 Nh7 17. hxg5 Nxg5 18.
f4 h4 19. Bh2 exf4 20. Bxf4 Bd7 $15 {[%cal Gh4h3,Ga8g8]}) 14... Bd7 15. Kc1 g5
{After connecting rooks, I couldn't find any reason to refrain from the
kingside expansion, as h2-h4 will not be a problem anymore.} 16. Bg3 Ne8 17.
Bd3 {But when I saw this move, I started being a bit worried. After evacuating
the e-file, White is ready to open the centre with f2-f4. While strategically
this looks risky, it could cause Black some trouble with his stability.} (17.
h4 Ng7 $15 {[%csl Gh8][%cal Gf7f5]}) (17. e4 Ng7 18. Nf1 f5 $15) 17... Ng7 18.
f4 Ba4 $1 $17 {An important move, made possible by the unusual development of
the queenside knight and forcing White to spoil his coordination due to the
congestion on the queenside.} 19. Nb3 ({After the game we concluded that} 19.
Qb2 {was better, even though we felt that White's position is unnatural. It
turns out that here, too, Black has an advantage.} exf4 20. exf4 Nh5 {This was
our mainline, but Black has several other good moves.} (20... Qe3 21. Bc2 Qxd2+
$1 22. Kxd2 Nxc4+ 23. Kc1 Nxb2 {[%csl Ga4] , with a clear extra pawn.}) ({
Best might be the developing} 20... Rae8 21. Nf3 Nh5 22. Re1 Qf6 {, but with
such poor coordination, White is busted.}) 21. Re1 Qd7 22. f5 Nxg3 23. hxg3
Rae8 24. Ne4 {We thought this would be more or less equal, but we were wrong.}
Qxf5 (24... Re5 25. g4 h5 {is also strong.}) 25. Rf1 Qe5 26. Rxf7+ Re7 $17)
19... exf4 ({My initial intention was} 19... e4 {, but then I noticed a
tactical possibility for White.} 20. Bxe4 {The right way to proceed is} (20.
Be2 Nf5 21. Bf2 gxf4 22. exf4 h5) 20... Rae8 $1 (20... Nxc4 21. Qd3 $1 {
[%cal Gb3c5]} ({I feared} 21. Na5 {, failing to notice} b5 $1 22. Qxa4 Qxe4 23.
Rxb5 Qxe3+ 24. Kc2 Na3+ 25. Qxa3 Qe2+ $17 {[%csl Gb5]}) 21... Bxb3 22. Rxb3 Nb6
23. c4 $44) 21. Bd3 Nh5 $17 {, which causes White's centre to collapse. But
despite my inaccurate calculation, my move was not a bit worse.}) 20. exf4 Nh5
21. Re1 Qf6 22. fxg5 Qxg5+ 23. Qd2 Nxg3 24. Qxg5 hxg5 25. hxg3 Rae8 $17 {
Black has the better structure on both wings and White still needs time to get
coordinated. Ionescu,C (2444)-Marin,M (2549) Calimanesti Caciulata 2016 (0-1,
33)} *

